# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: enzyme-catalysis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] In contrast, substances that bind directly to an enzyme's active site or the binding site of the endogenous ligand of a receptor are called **orthosteric** regulators or modulators.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] The site to which the effector binds is termed the *allosteric site* or *regulatory site*.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Allosteric sites allow effectors to bind to the protein, often resulting in a conformational change and/or a change in protein dynamics.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Effectors that enhance the protein's activity are referred to as *allosteric activators*, whereas those that decrease the protein's activity are called *allosteric inhibitors*.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Allosteric regulations are a natural example of control loops, such as feedback from downstream products or feedforward from upstream substrates.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Long-range allostery is especially important in cell signaling.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Allosteric regulation is also particularly important in the cell's ability to adjust enzyme activity.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] The term *allostery* comes from the Ancient Greek *allos* (ἄλλος), "other", and *stereos* (στερεός), "solid (object)".
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] This is in reference to the fact that the regulatory site of an allosteric protein is physically distinct from its active site.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Allostery contrasts with substrate presentation which requires no conformational change for an enzyme's activation.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] The term *orthostery* comes from the Ancient Greek orthós (ὀρθός) meaning "straight", "upright", "right" or "correct".
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Mechanism of Action: By occupying the active site, these inhibitors prevent the substrate from binding, thereby directly blocking the enzyme's catalytic activity.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Competitive Inhibition: Most orthosteric inhibitors compete with the substrate for the active site, which means their effectiveness can be reduced if substrate concentration increases.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Mechanism of Action: Binding to the allosteric site induces a conformational change in the enzyme that can either reduce the affinity of the active site for the substrate or alter the enzyme's catalytic activity.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] This indirect interference can inhibit the enzyme's function even if the substrate is present.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Non-Competitive Inhibition: Allosteric inhibitors often exhibit non-competitive inhibition, meaning their inhibitory effect is not dependent on the substrate concentration.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Many allosteric effects can be explained by the *concerted* MWC model put forth by Monod, Wyman, and Changeux, or by the sequential model (also known as the KNF model) described by Koshland, Nemethy, and Filmer.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Both postulate that protein subunits exist in one of two conformations, tensed (T) or relaxed (R), and that relaxed subunits bind substrate more readily than those in the tense state.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] The two models differ most in their assumptions about subunit interaction and the preexistence of both states.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] For proteins in which subunits exist in more than two conformations, the allostery landscape model described by Cuendet, Weinstein, and LeVine, can be used.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Allosteric regulation may be facilitated by the evolution of large-scale, low-energy conformational changes, which enables long-range allosteric interaction between distant binding sites.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] The concerted model of allostery, also referred to as the symmetry model or MWC model, postulates that enzyme subunits are connected in such a way that a conformational change in one subunit is necessarily conferred to all other subunits.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Thus, all subunits must exist in the same conformation.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] The model further holds that, in the absence of any ligand (substrate or otherwise), the equilibrium favors one of the conformational states, T or R.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] The sequential model of allosteric regulation holds that subunits are not connected in such a way that a conformational change in one induces a similar change in the others.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Thus, all enzyme subunits do not necessitate the same conformation.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Moreover, the sequential model dictates that molecules of a substrate bind via an induced fit protocol.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] While such an induced fit converts a subunit from the tensed state to relaxed state, it does not propagate the conformational change to adjacent subunits.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Instead, substrate-binding at one subunit only slightly alters the structure of other subunits so that their binding sites are more receptive to substrate.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] The morpheein model of allosteric regulation is a dissociative concerted model.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] A morpheein is a homo-oligomeric structure that can exist as an ensemble of physiologically significant and functionally different alternate quaternary assemblies.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Transitions between alternate morpheein assemblies involve oligomer dissociation, conformational change in the dissociated state, and reassembly to a different oligomer.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] The required oligomer disassembly step differentiates the morpheein model for allosteric regulation from the classic MWC and KNF models.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Porphobilinogen synthase (PBGS) is the prototype morpheein.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Ensemble models like the ensemble allosteric model and allosteric Ising model assume that each domain of the system can adopt two states similar to the MWC model.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] The allostery landscape model introduced by Cuendet, Weinstein, and LeVine allows for the domains to have any number of states and the contribution of a specific molecular interaction to a given allosteric coupling can be estimated using a rigorous set of rules.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Molecular dynamics simulations can be used to estimate a system's statistical ensemble so that it can be analyzed with the allostery landscape model.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Allosteric modulation is used to alter the activity of molecules and enzymes in biochemistry and pharmacology.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] For comparison, a typical drug is made to bind to the active site of an enzyme which thus prohibits binding of a substrate to that enzyme causing a decrease in enzyme activity.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Allosteric modulation occurs when an effector binds to an allosteric site (also known as a regulatory site) of an enzyme and alters the enzyme activity.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Allosteric modulators are designed to fit the allosteric site to cause a conformational change of the enzyme, in particular a change in the shape of the active site, which then causes a change in its activity.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] In contrast to typical drugs, modulators are not competitive inhibitors.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] They can be positive (activating) causing an increase of the enzyme activity or negative (inhibiting) causing a decrease of the enzyme activity.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] The use of allosteric modulation allows the control of the effects of specific enzyme activities; as a result, allosteric modulators are very effective in pharmacology.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] In a biological system, allosteric modulation can be difficult to distinguish from modulation by substrate presentation.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] An example of this model is seen with the enzyme pyruvate kinase of *Mycobacterium tuberculosis*, a bacterium that is perfectly suited to adapt to living in the macrophages of humans.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] The enzyme's sites serve as a communication between different substrates.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Sites like these also serve as a sensing mechanism for the enzyme's performance.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Positive allosteric modulation (also known as *allosteric activation*) occurs when the binding of one ligand enhances the affinity of other binding sites.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] An example is the binding of oxygen molecules to hemoglobin, where oxygen is both the physiological ligand and the modulator (or effector).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Here, the allosteric, or "other", site is the equivalent binding site of another protein subunit.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] The binding of oxygen to one subunit induces a conformational change in that subunit that interacts with the remaining binding sites to enhance *their* oxygen affinity.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] This type of allosteric modulation is also known as homotropic allostery or cooperativity as it describes the allosteric interaction between equivalent sites in an oligomeric protein.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Another example of allosteric activation is seen in cytosolic IMP-GMP specific 5'-nucleotidase II (cN-II), where the affinity for substrate GMP increases upon GTP binding at the dimer interface.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] As the two sites are not equivalent, this type of cooperativity is heterotropic.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Negative allosteric modulation (also known as *allosteric inhibition*) occurs when the binding of one ligand decreases the affinity for a ligand at other binding sites.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] For example, when 2,3-BPG binds to an allosteric site on hemoglobin, the affinity for oxygen of all subunits decreases.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Direct thrombin inhibitors provides an excellent example of negative allosteric modulation.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Allosteric inhibitors of thrombin have been discovered that could potentially be used as anticoagulants.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Another example is strychnine, a convulsant poison, which acts as an allosteric inhibitor of the glycine receptor.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Glycine is a major post-synaptic inhibitory neurotransmitter in mammalian spinal cord and brain stem.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Strychnine acts at a separate binding site on the glycine receptor in an allosteric manner; i.e., its binding lowers the affinity of the glycine receptor for glycine.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Thus, strychnine inhibits the action of an inhibitory transmitter, leading to convulsions.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Another instance in which negative allosteric modulation can be seen is between ATP and the enzyme phosphofructokinase within the negative feedback loop that regulates glycolysis.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Phosphofructokinase (generally referred to as PFK) is an enzyme that catalyses the third step of glycolysis: the phosphorylation of fructose-6-phosphate into fructose 1,6-bisphosphate.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] PFK can be allosterically inhibited by high levels of ATP within the cell.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] When ATP levels are high, ATP will bind to an allosteric site on phosphofructokinase, causing a change in the enzyme's three-dimensional shape.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] This change causes its affinity for substrate (fructose-6-phosphate and ATP) at the active site to decrease, and the enzyme is deemed inactive.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] This causes glycolysis to cease when ATP levels are high, thus conserving the body's glucose and maintaining balanced levels of cellular ATP.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] In this way, ATP serves as a negative allosteric modulator for PFK, despite the fact that it is also a substrate of the enzyme.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] A homotropic allosteric modulator is a substrate for its target protein, as well as a regulatory molecule of the protein's activity.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] It is typically an activator of the protein.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] For example, O2 and CO are homotropic allosteric modulators of hemoglobin.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Likewise, in IMP/GMP specific 5' nucleotidase, binding of one GMP molecule to a single subunit of the tetrameric enzyme leads to increased affinity for GMP by the subsequent subunits as revealed by sigmoidal substrate versus velocity plots.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] A heterotropic allosteric modulator is a regulatory molecule that is not the enzyme's substrate.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] It may be either an activator or an inhibitor of the enzyme.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] For example, H+, CO2, and 2,3-bisphosphoglycerate are heterotropic allosteric modulators of hemoglobin.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Once again, in IMP/GMP specific 5' nucleotidase, binding of GTP molecule at the dimer interface in the tetrameric enzyme leads to increased affinity for substrate GMP at the active site indicating towards K-type heterotropic allosteric activation.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] As has been amply highlighted above, some allosteric proteins can be regulated by both their substrates and other molecules.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Such proteins are capable of both homotropic and heterotropic interactions.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Some allosteric activators are referred to as "essential", or "obligate" activators, in the sense that in their absence, the activity of their target enzyme activity is very low or negligible, as is the case with N-acetylglutamate's activity on carbamoyl phosphate synthetase I, for example.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] A non-regulatory allosteric site is any non-regulatory component of an enzyme (or any protein), that is not itself an amino acid.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] For instance, many enzymes require sodium binding to ensure proper function.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] However, the sodium does not necessarily act as a regulatory subunit; the sodium is always present and there are no known biological processes to add/remove sodium to regulate enzyme activity.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Non-regulatory allostery could comprise any other ions besides sodium (calcium, magnesium, zinc), as well as other chemicals and possibly vitamins.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Allosteric modulation of a receptor results from the binding of allosteric modulators at a different site (a "regulatory site") from that of the endogenous ligand (an "active site") and enhances or inhibits the effects of the endogenous ligand.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Under normal circumstances, it acts by causing a conformational change in a receptor molecule, which results in a change in the binding affinity of the ligand.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] In this way, an allosteric ligand modulates the receptor's activation by its primary orthosteric ligand, and can be thought to act like a dimmer switch in an electrical circuit, adjusting the intensity of the response.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] For example, the GABAA receptor has two active sites that the neurotransmitter gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA) binds, but also has benzodiazepine and general anaesthetic agent regulatory binding sites.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] These regulatory sites can each produce positive allosteric modulation, potentiating the activity of GABA.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Diazepam is a positive allosteric modulator at the benzodiazepine regulatory site, and its antidote flumazenil is a receptor antagonist.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] More recent examples of drugs that allosterically modulate their targets include the calcium-mimicking cinacalcet and the HIV treatment maraviroc.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Allosteric proteins are involved in, and are central in many diseases, and allosteric sites may represent a novel drug target.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] There are a number of advantages in using allosteric modulators as preferred therapeutic agents over classic orthosteric ligands.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] For example, G protein-coupled receptor (GPCR) allosteric binding sites have not faced the same evolutionary pressure as **orthosteric sites** to accommodate an endogenous ligand, so are more diverse.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Therefore, greater GPCR selectivity may be obtained by targeting allosteric sites.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] This is particularly useful for GPCRs where selective orthosteric therapy has been difficult because of sequence conservation of the orthosteric site across receptor subtypes.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Also, these modulators have a decreased potential for toxic effects, since modulators with limited co-operativity will have a ceiling level to their effect, irrespective of the administered dose.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Another type of pharmacological selectivity that is unique to allosteric modulators is based on co-operativity.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] An allosteric modulator may display neutral co-operativity with an orthosteric ligand at all subtypes of a given receptor except the subtype of interest, which is termed "absolute subtype selectivity".
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] If an allosteric modulator does not possess appreciable efficacy, it can provide another powerful therapeutic advantage over orthosteric ligands, namely the ability to selectively tune up or down tissue responses only when the endogenous agonist is present.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Oligomer-specific small molecule binding sites are drug targets for medically relevant morpheeins.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] There are many synthetic compounds containing several noncovalent binding sites, which exhibit conformational changes upon occupation of one site.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Cooperativity between single binding contributions in such supramolecular systems is positive if occupation of one binding site enhances the affinity Δ*G* at a second site, and negative if the affinity isn't highered.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Most synthetic allosteric complexes rely on conformational reorganization upon the binding of one effector ligand which then leads to either enhanced or weakened association of second ligand at another binding site.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Conformational coupling between several binding sites is in artificial systems usually much larger than in proteins with their usually larger flexibility.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] The parameter which determines the efficiency (as measured by the ratio of equilibrium constants Krel = KA(E)/KA in presence and absence of an effector E ) is the conformational energy needed to adopt a closed or strained conformation for the binding of a ligand A.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] In many multivalent supramolecular systems direct interaction between bound ligands can occur, which can lead to large cooperativities.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Most common is such a direct interaction between ions in receptors for ion-pairs.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] This cooperativity is often also referred to as allostery, even though conformational changes here are not necessarily triggering binding events.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Allostery is a direct and efficient means for regulation of biological macromolecule function, produced by the binding of a ligand at an allosteric site topographically distinct from the orthosteric site.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Due to the often high receptor selectivity and lower target-based toxicity, allosteric regulation is also expected to play an increasing role in drug discovery and bioengineering.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] The AlloSteric Database (ASD) provides a central resource for the display, search and analysis of the structure, function and related annotation for allosteric molecules.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Currently, ASD contains allosteric proteins from more than 100 species and modulators in three categories (activators, inhibitors, and regulators).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Each protein is annotated with detailed description of allostery, biological process and related diseases, and each modulator with binding affinity, physicochemical properties and therapeutic area.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Integrating the information of allosteric proteins in ASD should allow the prediction of allostery for unknown proteins, to be followed with experimental validation.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] In addition, modulators curated in ASD can be used to investigate potential allosteric targets for a query compound, and can help chemists to implement structure modifications for novel allosteric drug design.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Not all protein residues play equally important roles in allosteric regulation.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] The identification of residues that are essential to allostery (so-called "allosteric residues") has been the focus of many studies, especially within the last decade.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] In part, this growing interest is a result of their general importance in protein science, but also because allosteric residues may be exploited in biomedical contexts.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Pharmacologically important proteins with difficult-to-target sites may yield to approaches in which one alternatively targets easier-to-reach residues that are capable of allosterically regulating the primary site of interest.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] These residues can broadly be classified as surface- and interior-allosteric amino acids.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/allosteric-regulation] Allosteric sites at the surface generally play regulatory roles that are fundamentally distinct from those within the interior; surface residues may serve as receptors or effector sites in allosteric signal transmission, whereas those within the interior may act to transmit such signals.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] A **cofactor** is a non-protein chemical compound or metallic ion that is required for an enzyme's role as a catalyst.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Cofactors can be considered "helper molecules" that assist in biochemical transformations.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] The rates at which these happen are characterized in an area of study called enzyme kinetics.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Cofactors typically differ from ligands in that they often derive their function by remaining bound.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Cofactors can be classified into two types: inorganic ions and complex organic molecules called coenzymes.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Coenzymes are mainly derived from vitamins and other organic essential nutrients in small amounts (some definitions limit the use of the term "cofactor" for inorganic substances; both types are included here).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Coenzymes are further divided into two types.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] The first is called a "prosthetic group", which consists of a coenzyme that is tightly (or even covalently and, therefore, permanently) bound to a protein.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] The second type of coenzymes are called "cosubstrates", and are transiently bound to the protein.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Cosubstrates may be released from a protein at some point, and then rebind later.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Both prosthetic groups and cosubstrates have the same function, which is to facilitate the reaction of enzymes and proteins.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] An inactive enzyme without the cofactor is called an apoenzyme, while the complete enzyme with cofactor is called a holoenzyme.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Some enzymes or enzyme complexes require several cofactors.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Organic cofactors are often vitamins or made from vitamins.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Many contain the nucleotide adenosine monophosphate (AMP) as part of their structures, such as ATP, coenzyme A, FAD, and NAD+.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] This common structure may reflect a common evolutionary origin as part of ribozymes in an ancient RNA world.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] It has been suggested that the AMP part of the molecule can be considered to be a kind of "handle" by which the enzyme can "grasp" the coenzyme to switch it between different catalytic centers.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Cofactors can be divided into two major groups: **organic** **cofactors**, such as flavin or heme; and **inorganic cofactors**, such as the metal ions Mg2+, Zn2+, Cu+, Mn2+ and iron–sulfur clusters.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Organic cofactors are sometimes further divided into *coenzymes* and *prosthetic groups*.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] The term coenzyme refers specifically to enzymes and, as such, to the functional properties of a protein.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] On the other hand, "prosthetic group" emphasizes the nature of the binding of a cofactor to a protein (tight or covalent) and, thus, refers to a structural property.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Different sources give slightly different definitions of coenzymes, cofactors, and prosthetic groups.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Some consider tightly bound organic molecules as prosthetic groups and not as coenzymes, while others define all non-protein organic molecules needed for enzyme activity as coenzymes, and classify those that are tightly bound as coenzyme prosthetic groups.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] A 1980 letter in *Trends in Biochemistry Sciences* noted the confusion in the literature and the essentially arbitrary distinction made between prosthetic groups and coenzymes group and proposed the following scheme.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Here, cofactors were defined as an additional substance apart from protein and substrate that is required for enzyme activity and a prosthetic group as a substance that undergoes its whole catalytic cycle attached to a single enzyme molecule.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] However, the author could not arrive at a single all-encompassing definition of a "coenzyme" and proposed that this term be dropped from use in the literature.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] The study of these cofactors falls under the area of bioinorganic chemistry.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] In nutrition, the list of essential trace elements reflects their role as cofactors.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] In humans this list commonly includes iron, magnesium, manganese, cobalt, copper, zinc, and molybdenum.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Although chromium deficiency causes impaired glucose tolerance, no human enzyme that uses this metal as a cofactor has been identified.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Iodine is also an essential trace element, but this element is used as part of the structure of thyroid hormones rather than as an enzyme cofactor.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Calcium is, therefore, a cell signaling ion, and not usually considered a cofactor of the enzymes it regulates.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] In many cases, the cofactor includes both an inorganic and organic component.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] One diverse set of examples is the heme proteins, which consist of a porphyrin ring coordinated to iron.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Iron–sulfur clusters are complexes of iron and sulfur atoms held within proteins by cysteinyl residues.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] They play both structural and functional roles, including electron transfer, redox sensing, and as structural modules.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Organic cofactors are small organic molecules (typically a molecular mass less than 1000 Da) that can be either loosely or tightly bound to the enzyme and directly participate in the reaction.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] In the latter case, when it is difficult to remove without denaturing the enzyme, it can be called a prosthetic group.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] There is no sharp division between loosely and tightly bound cofactors.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Many such as NAD+ can be tightly bound in some enzymes, while it is loosely bound in others.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Another example is thiamine pyrophosphate (TPP), which is tightly bound in transketolase or pyruvate decarboxylase, while it is less tightly bound in pyruvate dehydrogenase.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Other coenzymes, flavin adenine dinucleotide (FAD), biotin, and lipoamide, for instance, are tightly bound.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Tightly bound cofactors are, in general, regenerated during the same reaction cycle, while loosely bound cofactors can be regenerated in a subsequent reaction catalyzed by a different enzyme.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] In the latter case, the cofactor can also be considered a substrate or cosubstrate.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Vitamins can serve as precursors to many organic cofactors (e.g., vitamins B1, B2, B6, B12, niacin, folic acid) or as coenzymes themselves (e.g., vitamin C).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] However, vitamins do have other functions in the body.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Many organic cofactors also contain a nucleotide, such as the electron carriers NAD and FAD, and coenzyme A, which carries acyl groups.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Most of these cofactors are found in a huge variety of species, and some are universal to all forms of life.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] An exception to this wide distribution is a group of unique cofactors that evolved in methanogens, which are restricted to this group of archaea.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Although enzyme catalyzed industrial processes are highly efficient, some of the enzymes are dependent on nicotinamide cofactors (NADH/NAD+, NADP/NAPH).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Due to the high price of such cofactors, these processes would not be economically competitive.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Recently, some synthetic organic compounds were identified as economically promising biomimetic counterparts of natural cofactors.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Metabolism involves a vast array of chemical reactions, but most fall under a few basic types of reactions that involve the transfer of functional groups.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] This common chemistry allows cells to use a small set of metabolic intermediates to carry chemical groups between different reactions.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] These group-transfer intermediates are the loosely bound organic cofactors, often called coenzymes.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Each class of group-transfer reaction is carried out by a particular cofactor, which is the substrate for a set of enzymes that produce it, and a set of enzymes that consume it.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] An example of this are the dehydrogenases that use nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD+) as a cofactor.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Here, hundreds of separate types of enzymes remove electrons from their substrates and reduce NAD+ to NADH.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] This reduced cofactor is then a substrate for any of the reductases in the cell that require electrons to reduce their substrates.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Therefore, these cofactors are continuously recycled as part of metabolism.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] As an example, the total quantity of ATP in the human body is about 0.1 mole.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] This ATP is constantly being broken down into ADP, and then converted back into ATP.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Thus, at any given time, the total amount of ATP + ADP remains fairly constant.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] The energy used by human cells requires the hydrolysis of 100 to 150 moles of ATP daily, which is around 50 to 75 kg.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] In typical situations, humans use up their body weight of ATP over the course of the day.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] This means that each ATP molecule is recycled 1000 to 1500 times daily.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Organic cofactors, such as ATP and NADH, are present in all known forms of life and form a core part of metabolism.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Such universal conservation indicates that these molecules evolved very early in the development of living things.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] At least some of the current set of cofactors may, therefore, have been present in the last universal ancestor, which lived about 4 billion years ago.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Organic cofactors may have been present even earlier in the history of life on Earth.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] The nucleotide adenosine is a cofactor for many basic metabolic enzymes such as transferases.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Adenosine-based cofactors may have acted as adaptors that allowed enzymes and ribozymes to bind new cofactors through small modifications in existing adenosine-binding domains, which had originally evolved to bind a different cofactor.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] This process of adapting a pre-evolved structure for a novel use is known as *exaptation*.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] The first organic cofactor to be discovered was NAD+, which was identified by Arthur Harden and William Young 1906.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] They noticed that adding boiled and filtered yeast extract greatly accelerated alcoholic fermentation in unboiled yeast extracts.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] They called the unidentified factor responsible for this effect a *coferment*.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Through a long and difficult purification from yeast extracts, this heat-stable factor was identified as a nucleotide sugar phosphate by Hans von Euler-Chelpin.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Other cofactors were identified throughout the early 20th century, with ATP being isolated in 1929 by Karl Lohmann, and coenzyme A being discovered in 1945 by Fritz Albert Lipmann.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] The functions of these molecules were at first mysterious, but, in 1936, Otto Heinrich Warburg identified the function of NAD+ in hydride transfer.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] This discovery was followed in the early 1940s by the work of Herman Kalckar, who established the link between the oxidation of sugars and the generation of ATP.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] This confirmed the central role of ATP in energy transfer that had been proposed by Fritz Albert Lipmann in 1941.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Later, in 1949, Morris Friedkin and Albert L.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Lehninger proved that NAD+ linked metabolic pathways such as the citric acid cycle and the synthesis of ATP.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] In a number of enzymes, the moiety that acts as a cofactor is formed by post-translational modification of a part of the protein sequence.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] This often replaces the need for an external binding factor, such as a metal ion, for protein function.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Potential modifications could be oxidation of aromatic residues, binding between residues, cleavage or ring-forming.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] These alterations are distinct from other post-translation protein modifications, such as phosphorylation, methylation, or glycosylation in that the amino acids typically acquire new functions.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] This increases the functionality of the protein; unmodified amino acids are typically limited to acid-base reactions, and the alteration of resides can give the protein electrophilic sites or the ability to stabilize free radicals.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Examples of cofactor production include tryptophan tryptophylquinone (TTQ), derived from two tryptophan side chains, and 4-methylidene-imidazole-5-one (MIO), derived from an Ala-Ser-Gly motif.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Characterization of protein-derived cofactors is conducted using X-ray crystallography and mass spectroscopy; structural data is necessary because sequencing does not readily identify the altered sites.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] The term is used in other areas of biology to refer more broadly to non-protein (or even protein) molecules that either activate, inhibit, or are required for the protein to function.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] For example, ligands such as hormones that bind to and activate receptor proteins are termed cofactors or coactivators, whereas molecules that inhibit receptor proteins are termed corepressors.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] One such example is the G protein-coupled receptor family of receptors, which are frequently found in sensory neurons.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] Ligand binding to the receptors activates the G protein, which then activates an enzyme to activate the effector.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/cofactor-biochemistry] In order to avoid confusion, it has been suggested that such proteins that have ligand-binding mediated activation or repression be referred to as coregulators.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Most enzymes are made predominantly of proteins, either a single protein chain or many such chains in a multi-subunit complex.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Enzymes often also incorporate non-protein components, such as metal ions or specialized organic molecules known as cofactor (e.g. adenosine triphosphate).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Many cofactors are vitamins, and their role as vitamins is directly linked to their use in the catalysis of biological process within metabolism.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Catalysis of biochemical reactions in the cell is vital since many but not all metabolically essential reactions have very low rates when uncatalysed.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] One driver of protein evolution is the optimization of such catalytic activities, although only the most crucial enzymes operate near catalytic efficiency limits, and many enzymes are far from optimal.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Mechanisms of enzyme catalysis vary, but are all similar in principle to other types of chemical catalysis in that the crucial factor is a reduction of energy barrier(s) separating the reactants (or substrates) from the products.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] The reduction of activation energy (*E*a) increases the fraction of reactant molecules that can overcome this barrier and form the product.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] An important principle is that since they only reduce energy barriers between products and reactants, enzymes always catalyze reactions in both directions, and cannot drive a reaction forward or affect the equilibrium position – only the speed with which is it achieved.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] As with other catalysts, the enzyme is not consumed or changed by the reaction (as a substrate is) but is recycled such that a single enzyme performs many rounds of catalysis.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Enzymes are often highly specific, i.e. they only act on particular substrates, sometimes only one.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Others show group specificity and can act on similar but not identical chemical groups such as peptide bonds.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Many enzymes have stereochemical specificity and act on one stereoisomer but not another.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] The classic model for the enzyme-substrate interaction is the induced fit model.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] This model proposes that the initial interaction between enzyme and substrate is relatively weak, but that these weak interactions rapidly induce conformational changes in the enzyme that strengthen binding.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] The advantages of the induced fit mechanism arise due to the stabilizing effect of strong enzyme binding.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] There are two mechanisms of substrate binding: uniform binding, which has strong substrate binding, and differential binding, which has strong transition state binding.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] The stabilizing effect of uniform binding increases both substrate and transition state binding affinity, while differential binding increases only transition state binding affinity.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Both are used by enzymes and have been evolutionarily chosen to minimize the activation energy of the reaction.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Enzymes that are saturated, that is, have a high affinity substrate binding, require differential binding to reduce the energy of activation, whereas small substrate unbound enzymes may use either differential or uniform binding.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] These effects have led to most proteins using the differential binding mechanism to reduce the energy of activation, so most substrates have high affinity for the enzyme while in the transition state.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Differential binding is carried out by the induced fit mechanism – the substrate first binds weakly, then the enzyme changes conformation increasing the affinity to the transition state and stabilizing it, so reducing the activation energy to reach it.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] The induced fit concept cannot be used to rationalize catalysis.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] That is, the chemical catalysis is defined as the reduction of *E*a‡ (when the system is already in the ES‡) relative to *E*a‡ in the uncatalyzed reaction in water (without the enzyme).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] The induced fit only suggests that the barrier is lower in the closed form of the enzyme but does not tell us what the reason for the barrier reduction is.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Induced fit may be beneficial to the fidelity of molecular recognition in the presence of competition and noise via the conformational proofreading mechanism.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] However, the role of induced fit in controlling replication fidelity has been questioned and remains poorly defined.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Experimental and theoretical analyses have suggested that induced fit alone does not provide a sufficient explanation for high replication fidelity.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] These conformational changes also bring catalytic residues in the active site close to the chemical bonds in the substrate that will be altered in the reaction.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] After binding takes place, one or more mechanisms of catalysis lowers the energy of the reaction's transition state, by providing an alternative chemical pathway for the reaction.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Enzyme-substrate interactions align the reactive chemical groups and hold them close together in an optimal geometry, which increases the rate of the reaction.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] This reduces the entropy of the reactants and thus makes addition or transfer reactions less unfavorable, since a reduction in the overall entropy when two reactants become a single product.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] However this is a general effect and is seen in non-addition or transfer reactions where it occurs due to an increase in the "effective concentration" of the reagents.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] This is understood when considering how increases in concentration leads to increases in reaction rate: essentially when the reactants are more concentrated, they collide more often and so react more often.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] In enzyme catalysis, the binding of the reagents to the enzyme restricts the conformational space of the reactants, holding them in the 'proper orientation' and close to each other, so that they collide more frequently, of an with the correct geometry, to facilitate the desired reaction.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] The "effective concentration" is the concentration the reactant would have to be, free in solution, to experiences the same collisional frequency.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Often such theoretical effective concentrations are unphysical and impossible to realize in reality – which is a testament to the great catalytic power of many enzymes, with massive rate increases over the uncatalyzed state.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] However, the situation might be more complex, since modern computational studies have established that traditional examples of proximity effects cannot be related directly to enzyme entropic effects.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Also, the original entropic proposal has been found to largely overestimate the contribution of orientation entropy to catalysis.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Proton donors and acceptors, i.e. acids and base may donate and accept protons in order to stabilize developing charges in the transition state.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] This is related to the overall principle of catalysis, that of reducing energy barriers, since in general transition states are high energy states, and by stabilizing them this high energy is reduced, lowering the barrier.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] A key feature of enzyme catalysis over many non-biological catalysis, is that both acid and base catalysis can be combined in the same reaction.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] In many abiotic systems, acids (large [H+]) or bases ( large concentration H+ sinks, or species with electron pairs) can increase the rate of the reaction; but of course the environment can only have one overall pH (measure of acidity or basicity (alkalinity)).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] However, since enzymes are large molecules, they can position both acid groups and basic groups in their active site to interact with their substrates, and employ both modes independent of the bulk pH.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Often general acid or base catalysis is employed to activate nucleophile and/or electrophile groups, or to stabilize leaving groups.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Many amino acids with acidic or basic groups are this employed in the active site, such as the glutamic and aspartic acid, histidine, cystine, tyrosine, lysine and arginine, as well as serine and threonine.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] In addition, the peptide backbone, with carbonyl and amide N groups is often employed.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Cystine and Histidine are very commonly involved, since they both have a pKa close to neutral pH and can therefore both accept and donate protons.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Many reaction mechanisms involving acid/base catalysis assume a substantially altered pKa.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] This alteration of pKa is possible through the local environment of the residue.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] pKa can also be influenced significantly by the surrounding environment, to the extent that residues which are basic in solution may act as proton donors, and vice versa.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] The modification of the pKa's is a pure part of the electrostatic mechanism.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] The catalytic effect of the above example is mainly associated with the reduction of the pKa of the oxyanion and the increase in the pKa of the histidine, while the proton transfer from the serine to the histidine is not catalyzed significantly since it is not the rate determining barrier.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Note that in the example shown, the histidine conjugate acid acts as a general acid catalyst for the subsequent loss of the amine from a tetrahedral intermediate.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Evidence supporting this proposed mechanism (Figure 4 in Ref.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Stabilization of charged transition states can also be by residues in the active site forming ionic bonds (or partial ionic charge interactions) with the intermediate.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] These bonds can either come from acidic or basic side chains found on amino acids such as lysine, arginine, aspartic acid or glutamic acid or come from metal cofactors such as zinc.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Metal ions are particularly effective and can reduce the pKa of water enough to make it an effective nucleophile.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Systematic computer simulation studies have established that electrostatic effects give, by far, the largest contribution to catalysis, and can increase the rate of reaction by a factor of up to 107.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] In particular, it has been found that enzymes provide an environment which is more polar than water, and that ionic transition states are stabilized by fixed dipoles.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] This is very different from transition state stabilization in water, where the water molecules must pay with "reorganization energy" in order to stabilize ionic and charged states.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Thus, catalysis is associated with the fact that the enzyme polar groups are preorganized.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] The magnitude of the electrostatic field exerted by an enzyme's active site has been shown to be highly correlated with the enzyme's catalytic rate enhancement.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Binding of substrate usually excludes water from the active site, thereby lowering the local dielectric constant to that of an organic solvent.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] This strengthens the electrostatic interactions between the charged/polar substrates and the active sites.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] In addition, studies have shown that the charge distributions about the active sites are arranged so as to stabilize the transition states of the catalyzed reactions.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] In several enzymes, these charge distributions apparently serve to guide polar substrates toward their binding sites so that the rates of these enzymatic reactions are greater than their apparent diffusion-controlled limits.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Describing the dielectric constant in the enzyme–substrate complex as a single, low macroscopic value represents a significant oversimplification.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] In practice, the effective macroscopic dielectric constant of proteins can be relatively high (see, for example,).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] What is most relevant is that enzyme active sites are highly polar environments, in which polar groups are preorganized to stabilize the transition state.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Covalent catalysis involves the substrate forming a transient covalent bond with residues in the enzyme active site or with a cofactor.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] This adds an additional covalent intermediate to the reaction, and helps to reduce the energy of later transition states of the reaction.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] The covalent bond must, at a later stage in the reaction, be broken to regenerate the enzyme.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] This mechanism is utilised by the catalytic triad of enzymes such as proteases like chymotrypsin and trypsin, where an acyl-enzyme intermediate is formed.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] An alternative mechanism is schiff base formation using the free amine from a lysine residue, as seen in the enzyme aldolase during glycolysis.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Some enzymes utilize non-amino acid cofactors such as pyridoxal phosphate (PLP) or thiamine pyrophosphate (TPP) to form covalent intermediates with reactant molecules.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Enzymes utilizing such cofactors include the PLP-dependent enzyme aspartate transaminase and the TPP-dependent enzyme pyruvate dehydrogenase.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Rather than lowering the activation energy for a reaction pathway, covalent catalysis provides an alternative pathway for the reaction (via to the covalent intermediate) and so is distinct from true catalysis.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] For example, the energetics of the covalent bond to the serine molecule in chymotrypsin should be compared to the well-understood covalent bond to the nucleophile in the uncatalyzed solution reaction.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] A metal ion in the active site participates in catalysis by coordinating charge stabilization and shielding.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Because of a metal's positive charge, only negative charges can be stabilized through metal ions.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] However, metal ions are advantageous in biological catalysis because they are not affected by changes in pH.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Metal ions can also act to ionize water by acting as a Lewis acid.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Metal ions may also be agents of oxidation and reduction.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] This is the principal effect of induced fit binding, where the affinity of the enzyme to the transition state is greater than to the substrate itself.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] This induces structural rearrangements which strain substrate bonds into a position closer to the conformation of the transition state, so lowering the energy difference between the substrate and transition state and helping catalyze the reaction.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] However, the strain effect is, in fact, a ground state destabilization effect, rather than transition state stabilization effect.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Furthermore, enzymes are very flexible and they cannot apply large strain effect.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] In addition to bond strain in the substrate, bond strain may also be induced within the enzyme itself to activate residues in the active site.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] These traditional "over the barrier" mechanisms have been challenged in some cases by models and observations of "through the barrier" mechanisms (quantum tunneling).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Some enzymes operate with kinetics which are faster than what would be predicted by the classical ΔG‡.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] In "through the barrier" models, a proton or an electron can tunnel through activation barriers.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Quantum tunneling for protons has been observed in tryptamine oxidation by aromatic amine dehydrogenase.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Quantum tunneling does not appear to provide a major catalytic advantage, since the tunneling contributions are similar in the catalyzed and the uncatalyzed reactions in solution.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] However, the tunneling contribution (typically enhancing rate constants by a factor of ~1000 compared to the rate of reaction for the classical 'over the barrier' route) is likely crucial to the viability of biological organisms.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] This emphasizes the general importance of tunneling reactions in biology.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] However, as stated above, this does not represent a true catalytic effect, since the same enhancement exists in the corresponding reference reaction in solution.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] In 1971-1972 the first quantum-mechanical model of enzyme catalysis was formulated.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] However, this study did not include any representation of the enzyme environment, nor did it provide a relevant potential energy surface.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Consequently, it cannot be considered a true quantum mechanical study of enzyme catalysis.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Such investigations became feasible only with the development of combined quantum mechanical/molecular mechanical (QM/MM) methods.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] The binding energy of the enzyme-substrate complex cannot be considered as an external energy which is necessary for the substrate activation.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] It may be seen from reaction (**1**) that the group X1 of the active enzyme appears in the product due to possibility of the exchange reaction inside enzyme to avoid both electrostatic inhibition and repulsion of atoms.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] So we represent the active enzyme as a powerful reactant of the enzymatic reaction.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] The reaction (**2**) shows incomplete conversion of the substrate because its group X2 remains inside enzyme.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] This approach as idea had formerly proposed relying on the hypothetical extremely high enzymatic conversions (catalytically perfect enzyme).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] The crucial point for the verification of the present approach is that the catalyst must be a complex of the enzyme with the transfer group of the reaction.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] This chemical aspect is supported by the well-studied mechanisms of the several enzymatic reactions.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Consider the reaction of peptide bond hydrolysis catalyzed by a pure protein α-chymotrypsin (an enzyme acting without a cofactor), which is a well-studied member of the serine proteases family, see.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] where S1 is a polypeptide, P1 and P2 are products.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] The first chemical step (**3**) includes the formation of a covalent acyl-enzyme intermediate.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] The second step (**4**) is the deacylation step.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] The group H+, initially found on the enzyme, but not in water, appears in the product before the step of hydrolysis, therefore it may be considered as an additional group of the enzymatic reaction.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Thus, the reaction (**3**) shows that the enzyme acts as a powerful reactant of the reaction.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] According to the proposed concept, the H transport from the enzyme promotes the first reactant conversion, breakdown of the first initial chemical bond (between groups P1 and P2).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] The step of hydrolysis leads to a breakdown of the second chemical bond and regeneration of the enzyme.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] The proposed chemical mechanism does not depend on the concentration of the substrates or products in the medium.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] However, a shift in their concentration mainly causes free energy changes in the first and final steps of the reactions (**1**) and (**2**) due to the changes in the free energy content of every molecule, whether S or P, in water solution.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] This approach is in accordance with the following mechanism of muscle contraction.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] The final step of ATP hydrolysis in skeletal muscle is the product release caused by the association of myosin heads with actin.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] The closing of the actin-binding cleft during the association reaction is structurally coupled with the opening of the nucleotide-binding pocket on the myosin active site.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Notably, the final steps of ATP hydrolysis include the fast release of phosphate and the slow release of ADP.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] The release of a phosphate anion from bound ADP anion into water solution may be considered as an exergonic reaction because the phosphate anion has low molecular mass.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Thus, we arrive at the conclusion that the primary release of the inorganic phosphate H2PO4− leads to transformation of a significant part of the free energy of ATP hydrolysis into the kinetic energy of the solvated phosphate, producing active streaming.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] This assumption of a local mechano-chemical transduction is in accord with Tirosh's mechanism of muscle contraction, where the muscle force derives from an integrated action of active streaming created by ATP hydrolysis.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] In reality, most enzyme mechanisms involve a combination of several different types of catalysis.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Triose phosphate isomerase (EC 5.3.1.1) catalyses the reversible interconversion of the two triose phosphates isomers dihydroxyacetone phosphate and D-glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Trypsin (EC 3.4.21.4) is a serine protease that cleaves protein substrates after lysine or arginine residues using a catalytic triad to perform covalent catalysis, and an oxyanion hole to stabilise charge-buildup on the transition states.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Aldolase (EC 4.1.2.13) catalyses the breakdown of fructose 1,6-bisphosphate (F-1,6-BP) into glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate and dihydroxyacetone phosphate (DHAP).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] The advent of single-molecule studies in the 2010s led to the observation that the movement of untethered enzymes increases with increasing substrate concentration and increasing reaction enthalpy.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Subsequent observations suggest that this increase in diffusivity is driven by transient displacement of the enzyme's center of mass, resulting in a "recoil effect that propels the enzyme".
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-catalysis] Similarity between enzymatic reactions (EC) can be calculated by using bond changes, reaction centres or substructure metrics (EC-BLAST Archived 30 May 2019 at the Wayback Machine).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] An **enzyme inhibitor** is a molecule that binds to an enzyme and blocks its activity.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Enzymes are proteins that speed up chemical reactions necessary for life, in which substrate molecules are converted into products.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] An enzyme facilitates a specific chemical reaction by binding the substrate to its active site, a specialized area on the enzyme that accelerates the most difficult step of the reaction.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] An enzyme inhibitor stops ("inhibits") this process, either by binding to the enzyme's active site (thus preventing the substrate itself from binding) or by binding to another site on the enzyme such that the enzyme's catalysis of the reaction is blocked.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Enzyme inhibitors may bind reversibly or irreversibly.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Irreversible inhibitors form a chemical bond with the enzyme such that the enzyme is inhibited until the chemical bond is broken.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] By contrast, reversible inhibitors bind non-covalently and may spontaneously leave the enzyme, allowing the enzyme to resume its function.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Reversible inhibitors produce different types of inhibition depending on whether they bind to the enzyme, the enzyme-substrate complex, or both.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Enzyme inhibitors play an important role in all cells, since they are generally specific to one enzyme each and serve to control that enzyme's activity.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] For example, enzymes in a metabolic pathway may be inhibited by molecules produced later in the pathway, thus curtailing the production of molecules that are no longer needed.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] This type of negative feedback is an important way to maintain balance in a cell.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Enzyme inhibitors also control essential enzymes such as proteases or nucleases that, if left unchecked, may damage a cell.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Many poisons produced by animals or plants are enzyme inhibitors that block the activity of crucial enzymes in prey or predators.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Many drug molecules are enzyme inhibitors that inhibit an aberrant human enzyme or an enzyme critical for the survival of a pathogen such as a virus, bacterium or parasite.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Examples include methotrexate (used in chemotherapy and in treating rheumatic arthritis) and the protease inhibitors used to treat HIV/AIDS.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Since anti-pathogen inhibitors generally target only one enzyme, such drugs are highly specific and generally produce few side effects in humans, provided that no analogous enzyme is found in humans.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] (This is often the case, since such pathogens and humans are genetically distant.) Medicinal enzyme inhibitors often have low dissociation constants, meaning that only a minute amount of the inhibitor is required to inhibit the enzyme.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] A low concentration of the enzyme inhibitor reduces the risk for liver and kidney damage and other adverse drug reactions in humans.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Hence the discovery and refinement of enzyme inhibitors is an active area of research in biochemistry and pharmacology.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Enzyme inhibitors are a chemically diverse set of substances that range in size from organic small molecules to macromolecular proteins.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Small molecule inhibitors include essential primary metabolites that inhibit upstream enzymes that produce those metabolites.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] This provides a negative feedback loop that prevents over production of metabolites and thus maintains cellular homeostasis (steady internal conditions).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Small molecule enzyme inhibitors also include secondary metabolites, which are not essential to the organism that produces them, but provide the organism with an evolutionary advantage, in that they can be used to repel predators or competing organisms or immobilize prey.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] In addition, many drugs are small molecule enzyme inhibitors that target either disease-modifying enzymes in the patient or enzymes in pathogens which are required for the growth and reproduction of the pathogen.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] In addition to small molecules, some proteins act as enzyme inhibitors.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] The most prominent example are serpins (**ser**ine **p**rotease **in**hibitors) which are produced by animals to protect against inappropriate enzyme activation and by plants to prevent predation.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Another class of inhibitor proteins is the ribonuclease inhibitors, which bind to ribonucleases in one of the tightest known protein–protein interactions.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] A special case of protein enzyme inhibitors are zymogens that contain an autoinhibitory N-terminal peptide that binds to the active site of enzyme that intramolecularly blocks its activity as a protective mechanism against uncontrolled catalysis.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] The N‑terminal peptide is cleaved (split) from the zymogen enzyme precursor by another enzyme to release an active enzyme.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] The binding site of inhibitors on enzymes is most commonly the same site that binds the substrate of the enzyme.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] These active site inhibitors are known as orthosteric ("regular" orientation) inhibitors.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] The mechanism of orthosteric inhibition is simply to prevent substrate binding to the enzyme through direct competition which in turn prevents the enzyme from catalysing the conversion of substrates into products.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Alternatively, the inhibitor can bind to a site remote from the enzyme active site.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] These are known as allosteric ("alternative" orientation) inhibitors.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Kinetic mechanisms for reversible inhibition.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Substrate (S) binding to enzyme (E) in blue, catalysis releasing product (P) in red, inhibitor (I) binding to enzyme in green.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Binding site in blue, substrate in black, inhibitor in green, and allosteric site in light green.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Competitive inhibitors usually bind to the active site.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Non-competitive bind to a remote (allosteric) site.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Uncompetitive inhibitors only bind once the substrate is bound, fully disrupting catalysis, and mixed inhibition is similar but with only partial disruption of catalysis.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Reversible inhibitors attach to enzymes with non-covalent interactions such as hydrogen bonds, hydrophobic interactions and ionic bonds.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Multiple weak bonds between the inhibitor and the enzyme active site combine to produce strong and specific binding.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] In contrast to irreversible inhibitors, reversible inhibitors generally do not undergo chemical reactions when bound to the enzyme and can be easily removed by dilution or dialysis.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] A special case is **covalent reversible inhibitors** that form a chemical bond with the enzyme, but the bond can be cleaved so the inhibition is fully reversible.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Reversible inhibitors are generally categorized into four types, as introduced by Cleland in 1963.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] They are classified according to the effect of the inhibitor on the *Vmax* (maximum reaction rate catalysed by the enzyme) and *Km* (the concentration of substrate resulting in half maximal enzyme activity) as the concentration of the enzyme's substrate is varied.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] In competitive inhibition the substrate and inhibitor cannot bind to the enzyme at the same time.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] This usually results from the inhibitor having an affinity for the active site of an enzyme where the substrate also binds; the substrate and inhibitor *compete* for access to the enzyme's active site.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] This type of inhibition can be overcome by sufficiently high concentrations of substrate (*Vmax* remains constant), i.e., by out-competing the inhibitor.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] However, the apparent *Km* will increase as it takes a higher concentration of the substrate to reach the *Km* point, or half the *Vmax*.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Competitive inhibitors are often similar in structure to the real substrate (see for example the "methotrexate versus folate" figure in the "Drugs" section).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] In uncompetitive inhibition the inhibitor binds only to the enzyme-substrate complex.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] In non-competitive inhibition the binding of the inhibitor to the enzyme reduces its activity but does not affect the binding of substrate.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] This type of inhibitor binds with equal affinity to the free enzyme as to the enzyme-substrate complex.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] It can be thought of as having the ability of competitive and uncompetitive inhibitors, but with no preference to either type.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] As a result, the extent of inhibition depends only on the concentration of the inhibitor.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] *Vmax* will decrease due to the inability for the reaction to proceed as efficiently, but *Km* will remain the same as the actual binding of the substrate, by definition, will still function properly.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] In mixed inhibition the inhibitor may bind to the enzyme whether or not the substrate has already bound.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Hence mixed inhibition is a combination of competitive and noncompetitive inhibition.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Furthermore, the affinity of the inhibitor for the free enzyme and the enzyme-substrate complex may differ.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] By increasing concentrations of substrate [S], this type of inhibition can be reduced (due to the competitive contribution), but not entirely overcome (due to the noncompetitive component).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Although it is possible for mixed-type inhibitors to bind in the active site, this type of inhibition generally results from an allosteric effect where the inhibitor binds to a different site on an enzyme.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Inhibitor binding to this allosteric site changes the conformation (that is, the tertiary structure or three-dimensional shape) of the enzyme so that the affinity of the substrate for the active site is reduced.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] These four types of inhibition can also be distinguished by the effect of increasing the substrate concentration [S] on the degree of inhibition caused by a given amount of inhibitor.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] For competitive inhibition the degree of inhibition is reduced by increasing [S], for noncompetitive inhibition the degree of inhibition is unchanged, and for uncompetitive (also called anticompetitive) inhibition the degree of inhibition increases with [S].
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Reversible inhibition can be described quantitatively in terms of the inhibitor's binding to the enzyme and to the enzyme-substrate complex, and its effects on the kinetic constants of the enzyme.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] In the classic Michaelis-Menten scheme (shown in the "inhibition mechanism schematic" diagram), an enzyme (E) binds to its substrate (S) to form the enzyme–substrate complex ES.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Upon catalysis, this complex breaks down to release product P and free enzyme.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] The inhibitor (I) can bind to either E or ES with the dissociation constants *K*i or *K*i', respectively.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] When an enzyme has multiple substrates, inhibitors can show different types of inhibition depending on which substrate is considered.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] This results from the active site containing two different binding sites within the active site, one for each substrate.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] For example, an inhibitor might compete with substrate A for the first binding site, but be a non-competitive inhibitor with respect to substrate B in the second binding site.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Traditionally reversible enzyme inhibitors have been classified as competitive, uncompetitive, or non-competitive, according to their effects on *K*m and *V*max.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] These three types of inhibition result respectively from the inhibitor binding only to the enzyme E in the absence of substrate S, to the enzyme–substrate complex ES, or to both.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] The division of these classes arises from a problem in their derivation and results in the need to use two different binding constants for one binding event.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] It is further assumed that binding of the inhibitor to the enzyme results in 100% inhibition and fails to consider the possibility of partial inhibition.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] The common form of the inhibitory term also obscures the relationship between the inhibitor binding to the enzyme and its relationship to any other binding term be it the Michaelis–Menten equation or a dose response curve associated with ligand receptor binding.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] This rearrangement demonstrates that similar to the Michaelis–Menten equation, the maximal rate of reaction depends on the proportion of the enzyme population interacting with its substrate.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] the effect of the inhibitor is a result of the percent of the enzyme population interacting with inhibitor.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] The only problem with this equation in its present form is that it assumes absolute inhibition of the enzyme with inhibitor binding, when in fact there can be a wide range of effects anywhere from 100% inhibition of substrate turn over to no inhibition.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] To account for this the equation can be easily modified to allow for different degrees of inhibition by including a delta *V*max term.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] This term can then define the residual enzymatic activity present when the inhibitor is interacting with individual enzymes in the population.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] However the inclusion of this term has the added value of allowing for the possibility of activation if the secondary *V*max term turns out to be higher than the initial term.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] To account for the possibly of activation as well the notation can then be rewritten replacing the inhibitor "I" with a modifier term (stimulator or inhibitor) denoted here as "X".
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] While this terminology results in a simplified way of dealing with kinetic effects relating to the maximum velocity of the Michaelis–Menten equation, it highlights potential problems with the term used to describe effects relating to the *K*m.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] The *K*m relating to the affinity of the enzyme for the substrate should in most cases relate to potential changes in the binding site of the enzyme which would directly result from enzyme inhibitor interactions.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] An enzyme inhibitor is characterised by its dissociation constant *K*i, the concentration at which the inhibitor half occupies the enzyme.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] In non-competitive inhibition the inhibitor can also bind to the enzyme-substrate complex, and the presence of bound substrate can change the affinity of the inhibitor for the enzyme, resulting in a second dissociation constant *K*i'.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Hence *K*i and *K*i' are the dissociation constants of the inhibitor for the enzyme and to the enzyme-substrate complex, respectively.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] The enzyme-inhibitor constant *K*i can be measured directly by various methods; one especially accurate method is isothermal titration calorimetry, in which the inhibitor is titrated into a solution of enzyme and the heat released or absorbed is measured.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] However, the other dissociation constant *K*i' is difficult to measure directly, since the enzyme-substrate complex is short-lived and undergoing a chemical reaction to form the product.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Hence, *K*i' is usually measured indirectly, by observing the enzyme activity under various substrate and inhibitor concentrations, and fitting the data via nonlinear regression to a modified Michaelis–Menten equation.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Thus, in the presence of the inhibitor, the enzyme's effective *K*m and *V*max become (α/α')*K*m and (1/α')*V*max, respectively.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] However, the modified Michaelis-Menten equation assumes that binding of the inhibitor to the enzyme has reached equilibrium, which may be a very slow process for inhibitors with sub-nanomolar dissociation constants.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] In these cases the inhibition becomes effectively irreversible, hence it is more practical to treat such tight-binding inhibitors as irreversible (see below).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] The effects of different types of reversible enzyme inhibitors on enzymatic activity can be visualised using graphical representations of the Michaelis–Menten equation, such as Lineweaver–Burk, Eadie-Hofstee or Hanes-Woolf plots.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] An illustration is provided by the three Lineweaver–Burk plots depicted in the *Lineweaver–Burk diagrams* figure.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] In the top diagram the competitive inhibition lines intersect on the *y*-axis, illustrating that such inhibitors do not affect *V*max.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] In the bottom diagram the non-competitive inhibition lines intersect on the *x*-axis, showing these inhibitors do not affect *K*m.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] However, since it can be difficult to estimate *K*i and *K*i' accurately from such plots, it is advisable to estimate these constants using more reliable nonlinear regression methods.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] The mechanism of partially competitive inhibition is similar to that of non-competitive, except that the EIS complex has catalytic activity, which may be lower or even higher (partially competitive activation) than that of the enzyme–substrate (ES) complex.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] This inhibition typically displays a lower *V*max, but an unaffected *K*m value.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Substrate or product inhibition is where either an enzymes substrate or product also act as an inhibitor.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] This inhibition may follow the competitive, uncompetitive or mixed patterns.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] In substrate inhibition there is a progressive decrease in activity at high substrate concentrations, potentially from an enzyme having two competing substrate-binding sites.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] At low substrate, the high-affinity site is occupied and normal kinetics are followed.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] However, at higher concentrations, the second inhibitory site becomes occupied, inhibiting the enzyme.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Product inhibition (either the enzyme's own product, or a product to an enzyme downstream in its metabolic pathway) is often a regulatory feature in metabolism and can be a form of negative feedback.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Slow-tight inhibition occurs when the initial enzyme–inhibitor complex EI undergoes conformational isomerism (a change in shape) to a second more tightly held complex, EI*, but the overall inhibition process is reversible.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] This manifests itself as slowly increasing enzyme inhibition.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Under these conditions, traditional Michaelis–Menten kinetics give a false value for *K*i, which is time–dependent.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] The true value of *K*i can be obtained through more complex analysis of the on (*k*on) and off (*k*off) rate constants for inhibitor association with kinetics similar to irreversible inhibition.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] TGDDF/GDDF multi-substrate adduct inhibitor.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Substrate analogue in black, cofactor analogue in blue, non-cleavable linker in red.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Multi-substrate analogue inhibitors are high affinity selective inhibitors that can be prepared for enzymes that catalyse reactions with more than one substrate by capturing the binding energy of each of those substrate into one molecule.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Here the subnanomolar dissociation constant (KD) of TGDDF was greater than predicted presumably due to entropic advantages gained and/or positive interactions acquired through the atoms linking the components.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] MAIs have also been observed to be produced in cells by reactions of pro-drugs such as isoniazid or enzyme inhibitor ligands (for example, PTC124) with cellular cofactors such as nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NADH) and adenosine triphosphate (ATP) respectively.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] As enzymes have evolved to bind their substrates tightly, and most reversible inhibitors bind in the active site of enzymes, it is unsurprising that some of these inhibitors are strikingly similar in structure to the substrates of their targets.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Inhibitors of dihydrofolate reductase (DHFR) are prominent examples.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Other examples of these substrate mimics are the protease inhibitors, a therapeutically effective class of antiretroviral drugs used to treat HIV/AIDS.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] The structure of ritonavir, a peptidomimetic (peptide mimic) protease inhibitor containing three peptide bonds, as shown in the "competitive inhibition" figure above.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] As this drug resembles the peptide that is the substrate of the HIV protease, it competes with the substrate in the enzyme's active site.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Enzyme inhibitors are often designed to mimic the transition state or intermediate of an enzyme-catalysed reaction.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] This ensures that the inhibitor exploits the transition state stabilising effect of the enzyme, resulting in a better binding affinity (lower *K*i) than substrate-based designs.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] An example of such a transition state inhibitor is the antiviral drug oseltamivir; this drug mimics the planar nature of the ring oxonium ion in the reaction of the viral enzyme neuraminidase.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] However, not all inhibitors are based on the structures of substrates.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] For example, the structure of another HIV protease inhibitor tipranavir is not based on a peptide and has no obvious structural similarity to a protein substrate.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] These non-peptide inhibitors can be more stable than inhibitors containing peptide bonds, because they will not be substrates for peptidases and are less likely to be degraded.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] In drug design it is important to consider the concentrations of substrates to which the target enzymes are exposed.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] For example, some protein kinase inhibitors have chemical structures that are similar to ATP, one of the substrates of these enzymes.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] However, drugs that are simple competitive inhibitors will have to compete with the high concentrations of ATP in the cell.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Protein kinases can also be inhibited by competition at the binding sites where the kinases interact with their substrate proteins, and most proteins are present inside cells at concentrations much lower than the concentration of ATP.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] As a consequence, if two protein kinase inhibitors both bind in the active site with similar affinity, but only one has to compete with ATP, then the competitive inhibitor at the protein-binding site will inhibit the enzyme more effectively.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Irreversible inhibitors bind to the enzyme's binding site then undergo a chemical reaction to form a covalent enzyme-inhibitor complex (EI*).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Binding site in blue, inhibitor in green.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Irreversible inhibitors covalently bind to an enzyme, and this type of inhibition can therefore not be readily reversed.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Irreversible inhibitors often contain reactive functional groups such as nitrogen mustards, aldehydes, haloalkanes, alkenes, Michael acceptors, phenyl sulfonates, or fluorophosphonates.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] These electrophilic groups react with amino acid side chains to form covalent adducts.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] The residues modified are those with side chains containing nucleophiles such as hydroxyl or sulfhydryl groups; these include the amino acids serine (that reacts with DFP, see the "DFP reaction" diagram), and also cysteine, threonine, or tyrosine.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Irreversible inhibition is different from irreversible enzyme inactivation.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Irreversible inhibitors are generally specific for one class of enzyme and do not inactivate all proteins; they do not function by destroying protein structure but by specifically altering the active site of their target.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] For example, extremes of pH or temperature usually cause denaturation of all protein structure, but this is a non-specific effect.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Similarly, some non-specific chemical treatments destroy protein structure: for example, heating in concentrated hydrochloric acid will hydrolyse the peptide bonds holding proteins together, releasing free amino acids.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Irreversible inhibitors display time-dependent inhibition and their potency therefore cannot be characterised by an IC50 value.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] This is because the amount of active enzyme at a given concentration of irreversible inhibitor will be different depending on how long the inhibitor is pre-incubated with the enzyme.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Instead, *k*obs/[*I*] values are used, where *k*obs is the observed pseudo-first order rate of inactivation (obtained by plotting the log of % activity versus time) and [*I*] is the concentration of inhibitor.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] The *k*obs/[*I*] parameter is valid as long as the inhibitor does not saturate binding with the enzyme (in which case *k*obs = *k*inact) where *k*inact is the rate of inactivation.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Kinetic mechanism for irreversible inhibition.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Substrate binding in blue, catalysis in red, inhibitor binding in green, inactivation reaction in dark green.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Irreversible inhibitors first form a reversible non-covalent complex with the enzyme (EI or ESI).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Subsequently, a chemical reaction occurs between the enzyme and inhibitor to produce the covalently modified "dead-end complex" EI* (an irreversible covalent complex).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] The rate at which EI* is formed is called the inactivation rate or *k*inact.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Since formation of EI may compete with ES, binding of irreversible inhibitors can be prevented by competition either with substrate or with a second, reversible inhibitor.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] This protection effect is good evidence of a specific reaction of the irreversible inhibitor with the active site.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] The binding and inactivation steps of this reaction are investigated by incubating the enzyme with inhibitor and assaying the amount of activity remaining over time.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] The activity will be decreased in a time-dependent manner, usually following exponential decay.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Fitting these data to a rate equation gives the rate of inactivation at this concentration of inhibitor.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] This is done at several different concentrations of inhibitor.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] If a reversible EI complex is involved the inactivation rate will be saturable and fitting this curve will give *k*inact and *K*i.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Another method that is widely used in these analyses is mass spectrometry.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Here, accurate measurement of the mass of the unmodified native enzyme and the inactivated enzyme gives the increase in mass caused by reaction with the inhibitor and shows the stoichiometry of the reaction.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] This is usually done using a MALDI-TOF mass spectrometer.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] In a complementary technique, peptide mass fingerprinting involves digestion of the native and modified protein with a protease such as trypsin.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] This will produce a set of peptides that can be analysed using a mass spectrometer.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] The peptide that changes in mass after reaction with the inhibitor will be the one that contains the site of modification.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Not all irreversible inhibitors form covalent adducts with their enzyme targets.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Some reversible inhibitors bind so tightly to their target enzyme that they are essentially irreversible.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] These tight-binding inhibitors may show kinetics similar to covalent irreversible inhibitors.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] In these cases some of these inhibitors rapidly bind to the enzyme in a low-affinity EI complex and this then undergoes a slower rearrangement to a very tightly bound EI* complex (see the "irreversible inhibition mechanism" diagram).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] This kinetic behaviour is called slow-binding.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] This slow rearrangement after binding often involves a conformational change as the enzyme "clamps down" around the inhibitor molecule.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Examples of slow-binding inhibitors include some important drugs, such methotrexate, allopurinol, and the activated form of acyclovir.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Diisopropylfluorophosphate (DFP) is an example of an irreversible protease inhibitor (see the "DFP reaction" diagram).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] The enzyme hydrolyses the phosphorus–fluorine bond, but the phosphate residue remains bound to the serine in the active site, deactivating it.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Similarly, DFP also reacts with the active site of acetylcholine esterase in the synapses of neurons, and consequently is a potent neurotoxin, with a lethal dose of less than 100 mg.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Suicide inhibition is an unusual type of irreversible inhibition where the enzyme converts the inhibitor into a reactive form in its active site.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] An example is the inhibitor of polyamine biosynthesis, α-difluoromethylornithine (DFMO), which is an analogue of the amino acid ornithine, and is used to treat African trypanosomiasis (sleeping sickness).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Ornithine decarboxylase can catalyse the decarboxylation of DFMO instead of ornithine (see the "DFMO inhibitor mechanism" diagram).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] However, this decarboxylation reaction is followed by the elimination of a fluorine atom, which converts this catalytic intermediate into a conjugated imine, a highly electrophilic species.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] This reactive form of DFMO then reacts with either a cysteine or lysine residue in the active site to irreversibly inactivate the enzyme.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Since irreversible inhibition often involves the initial formation of a non-covalent enzyme inhibitor (EI) complex, it is sometimes possible for an inhibitor to bind to an enzyme in more than one way.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] For example, in the figure showing trypanothione reductase from the human protozoan parasite *Trypanosoma cruzi*, two molecules of an inhibitor called *quinacrine mustard* are bound in its active site.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] The top molecule is bound reversibly, but the lower one is bound covalently as it has reacted with an amino acid residue through its nitrogen mustard group.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Enzyme inhibitors are found in nature and also produced artificially in the laboratory.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Naturally occurring enzyme inhibitors regulate many metabolic processes and are essential for life.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] In addition, naturally produced poisons are often enzyme inhibitors that have evolved for use as toxic agents against predators, prey, and competing organisms.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] These natural toxins include some of the most poisonous substances known.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Artificial inhibitors are often used as drugs, but can also be insecticides such as malathion, herbicides such as glyphosate, or disinfectants such as triclosan.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Other artificial enzyme inhibitors block acetylcholinesterase, an enzyme which breaks down acetylcholine, and are used as nerve agents in chemical warfare.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Enzyme inhibition is a common feature of metabolic pathway control in cells.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Metabolic flux through a pathway is often regulated by a pathway's metabolites acting as inhibitors and enhancers for the enzymes in that same pathway.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] The glycolytic pathway is a classic example.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] This catabolic pathway consumes glucose and produces ATP, NADH and pyruvate.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] A key step for the regulation of glycolysis is an early reaction in the pathway catalysed by phosphofructokinase‑1 (PFK1).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] When ATP levels rise, ATP binds an allosteric site in PFK1 to decrease the rate of the enzyme reaction; glycolysis is inhibited and ATP production falls.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] This negative feedback control helps maintain a steady concentration of ATP in the cell.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] However, metabolic pathways are not just regulated through inhibition since enzyme activation is equally important.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] With respect to PFK1, fructose 2,6-bisphosphate and ADP are examples of metabolites that are allosteric activators.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Physiological enzyme inhibition can also be produced by specific protein inhibitors.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] This mechanism occurs in the pancreas, which synthesises many digestive precursor enzymes known as zymogens.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Many of these are activated by the trypsin protease, so it is important to inhibit the activity of trypsin in the pancreas to prevent the organ from digesting itself.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] One way in which the activity of trypsin is controlled is the production of a specific and potent trypsin inhibitor protein in the pancreas.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] This inhibitor binds tightly to trypsin, preventing the trypsin activity that would otherwise be detrimental to the organ.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Although the trypsin inhibitor is a protein, it avoids being hydrolysed as a substrate by the protease by excluding water from trypsin's active site and destabilising the transition state.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Other examples of physiological enzyme inhibitor proteins include the barstar inhibitor of the bacterial ribonuclease barnase.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Animals and plants have evolved to synthesise a vast array of poisonous products including secondary metabolites, peptides and proteins that can act as inhibitors.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Natural toxins are usually small organic molecules and are so diverse that there are probably natural inhibitors for most metabolic processes.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] The metabolic processes targeted by natural poisons encompass more than enzymes in metabolic pathways and can also include the inhibition of receptor, channel and structural protein functions in a cell.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] For example, paclitaxel (taxol), an organic molecule found in the Pacific yew tree, binds tightly to tubulin dimers and inhibits their assembly into microtubules in the cytoskeleton.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Many natural poisons act as neurotoxins that can cause paralysis leading to death and function for defence against predators or in hunting and capturing prey.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Some of these natural inhibitors, despite their toxic attributes, are valuable for therapeutic uses at lower doses.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] An example of a neurotoxin are the glycoalkaloids, from the plant species in the family Solanaceae (includes potato, tomato and eggplant), that are acetylcholinesterase inhibitors.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Inhibition of this enzyme causes an uncontrolled increase in the acetylcholine neurotransmitter, muscular paralysis and then death.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Neurotoxicity can also result from the inhibition of receptors; for example, atropine from deadly nightshade (*Atropa belladonna*) that functions as a competitive antagonist of the muscarinic acetylcholine receptors.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Although many natural toxins are secondary metabolites, these poisons also include peptides and proteins.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] An example of a toxic peptide is alpha-amanitin, which is found in relatives of the death cap mushroom.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] This is a potent enzyme inhibitor, in this case preventing the RNA polymerase II enzyme from transcribing DNA.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] The algal toxin microcystin is also a peptide and is an inhibitor of protein phosphatases.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] This toxin can contaminate water supplies after algal blooms and is a known carcinogen that can also cause acute liver haemorrhage and death at higher doses.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Proteins can also be natural poisons or antinutrients, such as the trypsin inhibitors (discussed in the "metabolic regulation" section above) that are found in some legumes.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] A less common class of toxins are toxic enzymes: these act as irreversible inhibitors of their target enzymes and work by chemically modifying their substrate enzymes.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] An example is ricin, an extremely potent protein toxin found in castor oil beans.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] This enzyme is a glycosidase that inactivates ribosomes.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Since ricin is a catalytic irreversible inhibitor, this allows just a single molecule of ricin to kill a cell.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] The most common uses for enzyme inhibitors are as drugs to treat disease.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Many of these inhibitors target a human enzyme and aim to correct a pathological condition.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] For instance, aspirin is a widely used drug that acts as a suicide inhibitor of the cyclooxygenase enzyme.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] This inhibition in turn suppresses the production of proinflammatory prostaglandins and thus aspirin may be used to reduce pain, fever, and inflammation.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] As of 2017, an estimated 29% of approved drugs are enzyme inhibitors of which approximately one-fifth are kinase inhibitors.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] A notable class of kinase drug targets is the receptor tyrosine kinases which are essential enzymes that regulate cell growth; their over-activation may result in cancer.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Hence kinase inhibitors such as imatinib are frequently used to treat malignancies.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Janus kinases are another notable example of drug enzyme targets.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Inhibitors of Janus kinases block the production of inflammatory cytokines and hence these inhibitors are used to treat a variety of inflammatory diseases in including arthritis, asthma, and Crohn's disease.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] An example of the structural similarity of some inhibitors to the substrates of the enzymes they target is seen in the figure comparing the drug methotrexate to folic acid.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Folic acid is the oxidised form of the substrate of dihydrofolate reductase, an enzyme that is potently inhibited by methotrexate.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Methotrexate blocks the action of dihydrofolate reductase and thereby halts thymidine biosynthesis.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] This block of nucleotide biosynthesis is selectively toxic to rapidly growing cells, therefore methotrexate is often used in cancer chemotherapy.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] A common treatment for erectile dysfunction is sildenafil (Viagra).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] This compound is a potent inhibitor of cGMP specific phosphodiesterase type 5, the enzyme that degrades the signalling molecule cyclic guanosine monophosphate.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] This signalling molecule triggers smooth muscle relaxation and allows blood flow into the corpus cavernosum, which causes an erection.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Since the drug decreases the activity of the enzyme that halts the signal, it makes this signal last for a longer period of time.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Drugs are also used to inhibit enzymes needed for the survival of pathogens.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] For example, bacteria are surrounded by a thick cell wall made of a net-like polymer called peptidoglycan.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Many antibiotics such as penicillin and vancomycin inhibit the enzymes that produce and then cross-link the strands of this polymer together.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] This causes the cell wall to lose strength and the bacteria to burst.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] In the figure, a molecule of penicillin (shown in a ball-and-stick form) is shown bound to its target, the transpeptidase from the bacteria *Streptomyces* R61 (the protein is shown as a ribbon diagram).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Antibiotic drug design is facilitated when an enzyme that is essential to the pathogen's survival is absent or very different in humans.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Humans do not make peptidoglycan, therefore antibiotics that inhibit this process are selectively toxic to bacteria.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Selective toxicity is also produced in antibiotics by exploiting differences in the structure of the ribosomes in bacteria, or how they make fatty acids.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Drugs that inhibit enzymes needed for the replication of viruses are effective in treating viral infections.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Antiviral drugs include protease inhibitors used to treat HIV/AIDS and Hepatitis C, reverse-transcriptase inhibitors targeting HIV/AIDS, neuraminidase inhibitors targeting influenza, and terminase inhibitors targeting human cytomegalovirus.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Acetylcholinesterase (AChE) is an enzyme found in animals, from insects to humans.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] It is essential to nerve cell function through its mechanism of breaking down the neurotransmitter acetylcholine into its constituents, acetate and choline.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] This is somewhat unusual among neurotransmitters as most, including serotonin, dopamine, and norepinephrine, are absorbed from the synaptic cleft rather than cleaved.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] A large number of AChE inhibitors are used in both medicine and agriculture.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Reversible competitive inhibitors, such as edrophonium, physostigmine, and neostigmine, are used in the treatment of myasthenia gravis and in anaesthesia to reverse muscle blockade.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] The carbamate pesticides are also examples of reversible AChE inhibitors.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] The organophosphate pesticides such as malathion, parathion, and chlorpyrifos irreversibly inhibit acetylcholinesterase.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] The herbicide glyphosate is an inhibitor of 3-phosphoshikimate 1-carboxyvinyltransferase, other herbicides, such as the sulfonylureas inhibit the enzyme acetolactate synthase.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Both enzymes are needed for plants to make branched-chain amino acids.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Many other enzymes are inhibited by herbicides, including enzymes needed for the biosynthesis of lipids and carotenoids and the processes of photosynthesis and oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] New drugs are the products of a long drug development process, the first step of which is often the discovery of a new enzyme inhibitor.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] There are two principle approaches of discovering these inhibitors.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] The first general method is rational drug design based on mimicking the transition state of the chemical reaction catalysed by the enzyme.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] The designed inhibitor often closely resembles the substrate, except that the portion of the substrate that undergoes chemical reaction is replaced by a chemically stable functional group that resembles the transition state.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Since the enzyme has evolved to stabilise the transition state, transition state analogues generally possess higher affinity for the enzyme compared to the substrate, and therefore are effective inhibitors.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] The second way of discovering new enzyme inhibitors is high-throughput screening of large libraries of structurally diverse compounds to identify hit molecules that bind to the enzyme.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] This method has been extended to include virtual screening of databases of diverse molecules using computers, which are then followed by experimental confirmation of binding of the virtual screening hits.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Complementary approaches that can provide new starting points for inhibitors include fragment-based lead discovery and DNA Encoded Chemical Libraries (DEL).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Hits from any of the above approaches can be optimised to high affinity binders that efficiently inhibit the enzyme.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] Computer-based methods for predicting the binding orientation and affinity of an inhibitor for an enzyme such as molecular docking and molecular mechanics can be used to assist in the optimisation process.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] New inhibitors are used to obtain crystallographic structures of the enzyme in an inhibitor/enzyme complex to show how the molecule is binding to the active site, allowing changes to be made to the inhibitor to optimise binding in a process known as structure-based drug design.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme-inhibitor] This test and improve cycle is repeated until a sufficiently potent inhibitor is produced.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] An **enzyme** is a biological macromolecule, usually a protein, that acts as a biological catalyst, accelerating chemical reactions without being consumed in the process.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] The molecules on which enzymes act are called substrates, which are converted into products.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Nearly all metabolic processes within a cell depend on enzyme catalysis to occur at biologically relevant rates.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] A metabolic pathway is typically composed of a series of enzyme-catalyzed steps.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] The study of enzymes is known as *enzymology*, and a related field focuses on pseudoenzymes—proteins that have lost catalytic activity but may retain regulatory or scaffolding functions, often indicated by alterations in their amino acid sequences or unusual 'pseudocatalytic' behavior.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Enzymes are known to catalyze over 5,000 types of biochemical reactions.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Other biological catalysts include catalytic RNA molecules, or ribozymes, which are sometimes classified as enzymes despite being composed of RNA rather than protein.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] More recently, biomolecular condensates have been recognized as a third category of biocatalysts, capable of catalyzing reactions by creating interfaces and gradients—such as ionic gradients—that drive biochemical processes, even when their component proteins are not intrinsically catalytic.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Enzymes increase the reaction rate by lowering a reaction's activation energy, often by factors of millions.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] A striking example is orotidine 5′-phosphate decarboxylase, which accelerates a reaction that would otherwise take millions of years to occur in milliseconds.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Like all catalysts, enzymes do not affect the overall equilibrium of a reaction and are regenerated at the end of each cycle.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] What distinguishes them is their high specificity, determined by their unique three-dimensional structure, and their sensitivity to factors such as temperature and pH.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Enzyme activity can be enhanced by activators or diminished by inhibitors, many of which serve as drugs or poisons.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Outside optimal conditions, enzymes may lose their structure through denaturation, leading to loss of function.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Enzymes have widespread practical applications.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] In industry, they are used to catalyze the production of antibiotics and other complex molecules.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] In everyday life, enzymes in biological washing powders break down protein, starch, and fat stains, enhancing cleaning performance.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Papain and other proteolytic enzymes are used in meat tenderizers to hydrolyze proteins, improving texture and digestibility.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Their specificity and efficiency make enzymes indispensable in both biological systems and commercial processes.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] By the late 17th and early 18th centuries, the digestion of meat by stomach secretions and the conversion of starch to sugars by plant extracts and saliva were known but the mechanisms by which these occurred had not been identified.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] French chemist Anselme Payen was the first to discover an enzyme, diastase, in 1833.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] A few decades later, when studying the fermentation of sugar to alcohol by yeast, Louis Pasteur concluded that this fermentation was caused by a vital force contained within the yeast cells called "ferments", which were thought to function only within living organisms.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] In 1877, German physiologist Wilhelm Kühne (1837–1900) first used the term *enzyme*, which comes from Ancient Greek ἔνζυμον*(énzymon)* 'leavened, in yeast', to describe this process.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] The word *enzyme* was used later to refer to nonliving substances such as pepsin, and the word *ferment* was used to refer to chemical activity produced by living organisms.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Eduard Buchner submitted his first paper on the study of yeast extracts in 1897.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] In a series of experiments at the University of Berlin, he found that sugar was fermented by yeast extracts even when there were no living yeast cells in the mixture.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] He named the enzyme that brought about the fermentation of sucrose "zymase".
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] In 1907, he received the Nobel Prize in Chemistry for "his discovery of cell-free fermentation".
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Following Buchner's example, enzymes are usually named according to the reaction they carry out: the suffix *-ase* is combined with the name of the substrate (e.g., lactase is the enzyme that cleaves lactose) or to the type of reaction (e.g., DNA polymerase forms DNA polymers).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] The biochemical identity of enzymes was still unknown in the early 1900s.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Many scientists observed that enzymatic activity was associated with proteins, but others (such as Nobel laureate Richard Willstätter) argued that proteins were merely carriers for the true enzymes and that proteins *per se* were incapable of catalysis.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Sumner showed that the enzyme urease was a pure protein and crystallized it; he did likewise for the enzyme catalase in 1937.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] The conclusion that pure proteins can be enzymes was definitively demonstrated by John Howard Northrop and Wendell Meredith Stanley, who worked on the digestive enzymes pepsin (1930), trypsin and chymotrypsin.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] These three scientists were awarded the 1946 Nobel Prize in Chemistry.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] The discovery that enzymes could be crystallized eventually allowed their structures to be solved by x-ray crystallography.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] This was first done for lysozyme, an enzyme found in tears, saliva and egg whites that digests the coating of some bacteria; the structure was solved by a group led by David Chilton Phillips and published in 1965.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] This high-resolution structure of lysozyme marked the beginning of the field of structural biology and the effort to understand how enzymes work at an atomic level of detail.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Enzymes can be classified by two main criteria: either their enzymatic activity or their amino acid sequence similarity (and thus evolutionary relationship).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] An enzyme's name is often derived from its substrate or the chemical reaction it catalyzes, with the word ending in *-ase*.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Examples are lactase, alcohol dehydrogenase and DNA polymerase.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Different enzymes that catalyze the same chemical reaction are called isozymes.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] The International Union of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology have developed a nomenclature for enzymes, the EC numbers (for "Enzyme Commission").
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Each enzyme is described by "EC" followed by a sequence of four numbers which represent the hierarchy of enzymatic activity (from very general to very specific).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] That is, the first number broadly classifies the enzyme based on its mechanism while the other digits add more and more specificity.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] These sections are subdivided by other features such as the substrate, products, and chemical mechanism.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] An enzyme is fully specified by four numerical designations.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] For example, hexokinase (EC 2.7.1.1) is a transferase (EC 2) that adds a phosphate group (EC 2.7) to a hexose sugar, a molecule containing an alcohol group (EC 2.7.1).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] EC categories do not reflect sequence similarity.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] For instance, two ligases of the same EC number that catalyze exactly the same reaction can have completely different sequences.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Independent of their function, enzymes, like any other proteins, have been classified by their sequence similarity into numerous families.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] These families have been documented in dozens of different protein and protein family databases such as Pfam.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Unrelated enzymes that have the same enzymatic activity have been called *non-homologous isofunctional enzymes*.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Horizontal gene transfer may spread these genes to unrelated species, especially bacteria where they can replace endogenous genes of the same function, leading to hon-homologous gene displacement.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Enzymes are generally globular proteins, acting alone or in larger complexes.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] The sequence of the amino acids specifies the structure which in turn determines the catalytic activity of the enzyme.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Although structure determines function, a novel enzymatic activity cannot yet be predicted from structure alone.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Enzyme structures unfold (denature) when heated or exposed to chemical denaturants and this disruption to the structure typically causes a loss of activity.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Enzymes are usually much larger than their substrates.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Sizes range from just 62 amino acid residues, for the monomer of 4-oxalocrotonate tautomerase, to over 2,500 residues in the animal fatty acid synthase.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Only a small portion of their structure (around 2–4 amino acids) is directly involved in catalysis: the catalytic site.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] This catalytic site is located next to one or more binding sites where residues orient the substrates.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] The catalytic site and binding site together compose the enzyme's active site.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] The remaining majority of the enzyme structure serves to maintain the precise orientation and dynamics of the active site.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] In some enzymes, no amino acids are directly involved in catalysis; instead, the enzyme contains sites to bind and orient catalytic cofactors.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Enzyme structures may also contain allosteric sites where the binding of a small molecule causes a conformational change that increases or decreases activity.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] A small number of RNA-based biological catalysts called ribozymes exist, which again can act alone or in complex with proteins.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] The most common of these is the ribosome which is a complex of protein and catalytic RNA components.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Enzymes must bind their substrates before they can catalyze any chemical reaction.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Enzymes are usually very specific as to what substrates they bind and then the chemical reaction catalyzed.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Specificity is achieved by binding pockets with complementary shape, charge and hydrophilic/hydrophobic characteristics to the substrates.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Enzymes can therefore distinguish between very similar substrate molecules to be chemoselective, regioselective and stereospecific.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Some of the enzymes showing the highest specificity and accuracy are involved in the copying and expression of the genome.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Some of these enzymes have "proof-reading" mechanisms.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Here, an enzyme such as DNA polymerase catalyzes a reaction in a first step and then checks that the product is correct in a second step.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] This two-step process results in average error rates of less than 1 error in 100 million reactions in high-fidelity mammalian polymerases.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Similar proofreading mechanisms are also found in RNA polymerase, aminoacyl tRNA synthetases and ribosomes.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Conversely, some enzymes display enzyme promiscuity, having broad specificity and acting on a range of different physiologically relevant substrates.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Many enzymes possess small side activities which arose fortuitously (i.e. neutrally), which may be the starting point for the evolutionary selection of a new function.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] To explain the observed specificity of enzymes, in 1894 Emil Fischer proposed that both the enzyme and the substrate possess specific complementary geometric shapes that fit exactly into one another.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] This is often referred to as "the lock and key" model.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] This early model explains enzyme specificity, but fails to explain the stabilization of the transition state that enzymes achieve.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] In 1958, Daniel Koshland suggested a modification to the lock and key model: since enzymes are rather flexible structures, the active site is continuously reshaped by interactions with the substrate as the substrate interacts with the enzyme.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] As a result, the substrate does not simply bind to a rigid active site; the amino acid side-chains that make up the active site are molded into the precise positions that enable the enzyme to perform its catalytic function.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] In some cases, such as glycosidases, the substrate molecule also changes shape slightly as it enters the active site.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] The active site continues to change until the substrate is completely bound, at which point the final shape and charge distribution is determined.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Induced fit may enhance the fidelity of molecular recognition in the presence of competition and noise via the conformational proofreading mechanism.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Enzymes may use several of these mechanisms simultaneously.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] For example, proteases such as trypsin perform covalent catalysis using a catalytic triad, stabilize charge build-up on the transition states using an oxyanion hole, complete hydrolysis using an oriented water substrate.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Enzymes are not rigid, static structures; instead they have complex internal dynamic motions – that is, movements of parts of the enzyme's structure such as individual amino acid residues, groups of residues forming a protein loop or unit of secondary structure, or even an entire protein domain.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] These motions give rise to a conformational ensemble of slightly different structures that interconvert with one another at equilibrium.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Different states within this ensemble may be associated with different aspects of an enzyme's function.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] For example, different conformations of the enzyme dihydrofolate reductase are associated with the substrate binding, catalysis, cofactor release, and product release steps of the catalytic cycle, consistent with catalytic resonance theory.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] The transitions between the different conformations during the catalytic cycle involve internal viscoelastic motion that is facilitated by high-strain regions where amino acids are rearranged.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Substrate presentation is a process where the enzyme is sequestered away from its substrate.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Enzymes can be sequestered to the plasma membrane away from a substrate in the nucleus or cytosol.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Or within the membrane, an enzyme can be sequestered into lipid rafts away from its substrate in the disordered region.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] When the enzyme is released it mixes with its substrate.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Alternatively, the enzyme can be sequestered near its substrate to activate the enzyme.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] For example, the enzyme can be soluble and upon activation bind to a lipid in the plasma membrane and then act upon molecules in the plasma membrane.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Allosteric sites are pockets on the enzyme, distinct from the active site, that bind to molecules in the cellular environment.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] These molecules then cause a change in the conformation or dynamics of the enzyme that is transduced to the active site and thus affects the reaction rate of the enzyme.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] In this way, allosteric interactions can either inhibit or activate enzymes.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Allosteric interactions with metabolites upstream or downstream in an enzyme's metabolic pathway cause feedback regulation, altering the activity of the enzyme according to the flux through the rest of the pathway.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Some enzymes do not need additional components to show full activity.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Others require non-protein molecules called cofactors to be bound for activity.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Cofactors can be either inorganic (e.g., metal ions and iron–sulfur clusters) or organic compounds (e.g., flavin and heme).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] These cofactors serve many purposes; for instance, metal ions can help in stabilizing nucleophilic species within the active site.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Organic cofactors can be either coenzymes, which are released from the enzyme's active site during the reaction, or prosthetic groups, which are tightly bound to an enzyme.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Organic prosthetic groups can be covalently bound (e.g., biotin in enzymes such as pyruvate carboxylase).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] An example of an enzyme that contains a cofactor is carbonic anhydrase, which uses a zinc cofactor bound as part of its active site.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] These tightly bound ions or molecules are usually found in the active site and are involved in catalysis.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] For example, flavin and heme cofactors are often involved in redox reactions.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Enzymes that require a cofactor but do not have one bound are called *apoenzymes* or *apoproteins*.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] An enzyme together with the cofactor(s) required for activity is called a *holoenzyme* (or haloenzyme).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] The term *holoenzyme* can also be applied to enzymes that contain multiple protein subunits, such as the DNA polymerases; here the holoenzyme is the complete complex containing all the subunits needed for activity.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Coenzymes are small organic molecules that can be loosely or tightly bound to an enzyme.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Coenzymes transport chemical groups from one enzyme to another.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Examples include NADH, NADPH and adenosine triphosphate (ATP).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Some coenzymes, such as flavin mononucleotide (FMN), flavin adenine dinucleotide (FAD), thiamine pyrophosphate (TPP), and tetrahydrofolate (THF), are derived from vitamins.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] These coenzymes cannot be synthesized by the body *de novo* and closely related compounds (vitamins) must be acquired from the diet.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Since coenzymes are chemically changed as a consequence of enzyme action, it is useful to consider coenzymes to be a special class of substrates, or second substrates, which are common to many different enzymes.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] For example, about 1000 enzymes are known to use the coenzyme NADH.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Coenzymes are usually continuously regenerated and their concentrations maintained at a steady level inside the cell.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] For example, NADPH is regenerated through the pentose phosphate pathway and *S*-adenosylmethionine by methionine adenosyltransferase.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] This continuous regeneration means that small amounts of coenzymes can be used very intensively.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] For example, the human body turns over its own weight in ATP each day.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] As with all catalysts, enzymes do not alter the position of the chemical equilibrium of the reaction.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] In the presence of an enzyme, the reaction runs in the same direction as it would without the enzyme, just more quickly.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] The rate of a reaction is dependent on the activation energy needed to form the transition state which then decays into products.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Enzymes increase reaction rates by lowering the energy of the transition state.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] First, binding forms a low energy enzyme-substrate complex (ES).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Second, the enzyme stabilises the transition state such that it requires less energy to achieve compared to the uncatalyzed reaction (ES‡).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Finally the enzyme-product complex (EP) dissociates to release the products.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Enzymes can couple two or more reactions, so that a thermodynamically favorable reaction can be used to "drive" a thermodynamically unfavourable one so that the combined energy of the products is lower than the substrates.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] For example, the hydrolysis of ATP is often used to drive other chemical reactions.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] for an enzyme reaction showing the relation between the substrate concentration and reaction rate.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Enzyme kinetics is the investigation of how enzymes bind substrates and turn them into products.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] The rate data used in kinetic analyses are commonly obtained from enzyme assays.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] In 1913 Leonor Michaelis and Maud Leonora Menten proposed a quantitative theory of enzyme kinetics, which is referred to as Michaelis–Menten kinetics.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] The major contribution of Michaelis and Menten was to think of enzyme reactions in two stages.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] In the first, the substrate binds reversibly to the enzyme, forming the enzyme-substrate complex.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] This is sometimes called the Michaelis–Menten complex in their honor.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] The enzyme then catalyzes the chemical step in the reaction and releases the product.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Haldane, who derived kinetic equations that are still widely used today.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Enzyme rates depend on solution conditions and substrate concentration.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] To find the maximum speed of an enzymatic reaction, the substrate concentration is increased until a constant rate of product formation is seen.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] This is shown in the saturation curve on the right.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Saturation happens because, as substrate concentration increases, more and more of the free enzyme is converted into the substrate-bound ES complex.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] At the maximum reaction rate (*V*max) of the enzyme, all the enzyme active sites are bound to substrate, and the amount of ES complex is the same as the total amount of enzyme.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] The efficiency of an enzyme can be expressed in terms of *k*cat/*K*m.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] This is also called the specificity constant and incorporates the rate constants for all steps in the reaction up to and including the first irreversible step.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Because the specificity constant reflects both affinity and catalytic ability, it is useful for comparing different enzymes against each other, or the same enzyme with different substrates.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] The theoretical maximum for the specificity constant is called the diffusion limit and is about 108 to 109 (M−1 s−1).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] At this point every collision of the enzyme with its substrate will result in catalysis, and the rate of product formation is not limited by the reaction rate but by the diffusion rate.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Enzymes with this property are called *catalytically perfect* or *kinetically perfect*.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Example of such enzymes are triose-phosphate isomerase, carbonic anhydrase, acetylcholinesterase, catalase, fumarase, β-lactamase, and superoxide dismutase.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] The turnover of such enzymes can reach several million reactions per second.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Michaelis–Menten kinetics relies on the law of mass action, which is derived from the assumptions of free diffusion and thermodynamically driven random collision.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Many biochemical or cellular processes deviate significantly from these conditions, because of macromolecular crowding and constrained molecular movement.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] More recent, complex extensions of the model attempt to correct for these effects.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] (right) are very similar in structure (differences show in green).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] As a result, methotrexate is a competitive inhibitor of many enzymes that use folates.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Enzyme reaction rates can be decreased by various types of enzyme inhibitors.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] A competitive inhibitor and substrate cannot bind to the enzyme at the same time.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Often competitive inhibitors strongly resemble the real substrate of the enzyme.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] For example, the drug methotrexate is a competitive inhibitor of the enzyme dihydrofolate reductase, which catalyzes the reduction of dihydrofolate to tetrahydrofolate.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] The similarity between the structures of dihydrofolate and this drug are shown in the accompanying figure.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] This type of inhibition can be overcome with high substrate concentration.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] In some cases, the inhibitor can bind to a site other than the binding-site of the usual substrate and exert an allosteric effect to change the shape of the usual binding-site.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] A non-competitive inhibitor binds to a site other than where the substrate binds.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] The substrate still binds with its usual affinity and hence Km remains the same.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] However the inhibitor reduces the catalytic efficiency of the enzyme so that Vmax is reduced.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] In contrast to competitive inhibition, non-competitive inhibition cannot be overcome with high substrate concentration.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] An uncompetitive inhibitor cannot bind to the free enzyme, only to the enzyme-substrate complex; hence, these types of inhibitors are most effective at high substrate concentration.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] In the presence of the inhibitor, the enzyme-substrate complex is inactive.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] A mixed inhibitor binds to an allosteric site and the binding of the substrate and the inhibitor affect each other.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] The enzyme's function is reduced but not eliminated when bound to the inhibitor.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] This type of inhibitor does not follow the Michaelis–Menten equation.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] An irreversible inhibitor permanently inactivates the enzyme, usually by forming a covalent bond to the protein.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Penicillin and aspirin are common drugs that act in this manner.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] In many organisms, inhibitors may act as part of a feedback mechanism.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] If an enzyme produces too much of one substance in the organism, that substance may act as an inhibitor for the enzyme at the beginning of the pathway that produces it, causing production of the substance to slow down or stop when there is sufficient amount.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Major metabolic pathways such as the citric acid cycle make use of this mechanism.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Since inhibitors modulate the function of enzymes they are often used as drugs.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Many such drugs are reversible competitive inhibitors that resemble the enzyme's native substrate, similar to methotrexate above; other well-known examples include statins used to treat high cholesterol, and protease inhibitors used to treat retroviral infections such as HIV.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] A common example of an irreversible inhibitor that is used as a drug is aspirin, which inhibits the COX-1 and COX-2 enzymes that produce the inflammation messenger prostaglandin.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] For example, the poison cyanide is an irreversible enzyme inhibitor that combines with the copper and iron in the active site of the enzyme cytochrome c oxidase and blocks cellular respiration.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] As enzymes are made up of proteins, their actions are sensitive to change in many physio chemical factors such as pH, temperature, substrate concentration, etc.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] The following table shows pH optima for various enzymes.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Enzymes serve a wide variety of functions inside living organisms.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] They are indispensable for signal transduction and cell regulation, often via kinases and phosphatases.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] They also generate movement, with myosin hydrolyzing adenosine triphosphate (ATP) to generate muscle contraction, and also transport cargo around the cell as part of the cytoskeleton.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Other ATPases in the cell membrane are ion pumps involved in active transport.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Enzymes are also involved in more exotic functions, such as luciferase generating light in fireflies.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Viruses can also contain enzymes for infecting cells, such as the HIV integrase and reverse transcriptase, or for viral release from cells, like the influenza virus neuraminidase.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] An important function of enzymes is in the digestive systems of animals.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Enzymes such as amylases and proteases break down large molecules (starch or proteins, respectively) into smaller ones, so they can be absorbed by the intestines.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Starch molecules, for example, are too large to be absorbed from the intestine, but enzymes hydrolyze the starch chains into smaller molecules such as maltose and eventually glucose, which can then be absorbed.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Different enzymes digest different food substances.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] In ruminants, which have herbivorous diets, microorganisms in the gut produce another enzyme, cellulase, to break down the cellulose cell walls of plant fiber.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Several enzymes can work together in a specific order, creating metabolic pathways.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] In a metabolic pathway, one enzyme takes the product of another enzyme as a substrate.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] After the catalytic reaction, the product is then passed on to another enzyme.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Sometimes more than one enzyme can catalyze the same reaction in parallel; this can allow more complex regulation: with, for example, a low constant activity provided by one enzyme but an inducible high activity from a second enzyme.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Enzymes determine what steps occur in these pathways.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Without enzymes, metabolism would neither progress through the same steps and could not be regulated to serve the needs of the cell.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Most central metabolic pathways are regulated at a few steps, typically through enzymes whose activity involves the phosphorylation by ATP.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Because this reaction releases so much energy, other reactions that are thermodynamically unfavorable can be coupled to ATP hydrolysis, driving the overall series of linked metabolic reactions.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] There are five main ways that enzyme activity is controlled in the cell.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Enzymes can be either activated or inhibited by other molecules.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] For example, the end product(s) of a metabolic pathway are often inhibitors for one of the first enzymes of the pathway (usually the first irreversible step, called committed step), thus regulating the amount of end product made by the pathways.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Such a regulatory mechanism is called a negative feedback mechanism, because the amount of the end product produced is regulated by its own concentration.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Negative feedback mechanism can effectively adjust the rate of synthesis of intermediate metabolites according to the demands of the cells.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] This helps with effective allocations of materials and energy economy, and it prevents the excess manufacture of end products.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Like other homeostatic devices, the control of enzymatic action helps to maintain a stable internal environment in living organisms.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Examples of post-translational modification include phosphorylation, myristoylation and glycosylation.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] For example, in the response to insulin, the phosphorylation of multiple enzymes, including glycogen synthase, helps control the synthesis or degradation of glycogen and allows the cell to respond to changes in blood sugar.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Another example of post-translational modification is the cleavage of the polypeptide chain.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Chymotrypsin, a digestive protease, is produced in inactive form as chymotrypsinogen in the pancreas and transported in this form to the stomach where it is activated.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] This stops the enzyme from digesting the pancreas or other tissues before it enters the gut.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] This type of inactive precursor to an enzyme is known as a zymogen or proenzyme.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Enzyme production (transcription and translation of enzyme genes) can be enhanced or diminished by a cell in response to changes in the cell's environment.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] This form of gene regulation is called enzyme induction.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] For example, bacteria may become resistant to antibiotics such as penicillin because enzymes called beta-lactamases are induced that hydrolyse the crucial beta-lactam ring within the penicillin molecule.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Another example comes from enzymes in the liver called cytochrome P450 oxidases, which are important in drug metabolism.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Induction or inhibition of these enzymes can cause drug interactions.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Enzyme levels can also be regulated by changing the rate of enzyme degradation.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] The opposite of enzyme induction is enzyme repression.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Enzymes can be compartmentalized, with different metabolic pathways occurring in different cellular compartments.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] For example, fatty acids are synthesized by one set of enzymes in the cytosol, endoplasmic reticulum and Golgi and used by a different set of enzymes as a source of energy in the mitochondrion, through β-oxidation.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] In addition, trafficking of the enzyme to different compartments may change the degree of protonation (e.g., the neutral cytoplasm and the acidic lysosome) or oxidative state (e.g., oxidizing periplasm or reducing cytoplasm) which in turn affects enzyme activity.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] In contrast to partitioning into membrane bound organelles, enzyme subcellular localisation may also be altered through polymerisation of enzymes into macromolecular cytoplasmic filaments.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] In multicellular eukaryotes, cells in different organs and tissues have different patterns of gene expression and therefore have different sets of enzymes (known as isozymes) available for metabolic reactions.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] This provides a mechanism for regulating the overall metabolism of the organism.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] For example, hexokinase, the first enzyme in the glycolysis pathway, has a specialized form called glucokinase expressed in the liver and pancreas that has a lower affinity for glucose yet is more sensitive to glucose concentration.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] This enzyme is involved in sensing blood sugar and regulating insulin production.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Since the tight control of enzyme activity is essential for homeostasis, any malfunction (mutation, overproduction, underproduction or deletion) of a single critical enzyme can lead to a genetic disease.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] The malfunction of just one type of enzyme out of the thousands of types present in the human body can be fatal.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] An example of a fatal genetic disease due to enzyme insufficiency is Tay–Sachs disease, in which patients lack the enzyme hexosaminidase.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] One example of enzyme deficiency is the most common type of phenylketonuria.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Many different single amino acid mutations in the enzyme phenylalanine hydroxylase, which catalyzes the first step in the degradation of phenylalanine, result in build-up of phenylalanine and related products.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Some mutations are in the active site, directly disrupting binding and catalysis, but many are far from the active site and reduce activity by destabilising the protein structure, or affecting correct oligomerisation.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] This can lead to intellectual disability if the disease is untreated.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Another example is pseudocholinesterase deficiency, in which the body's ability to break down choline ester drugs is impaired.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Oral administration of enzymes can be used to treat some functional enzyme deficiencies, such as pancreatic insufficiency and lactose intolerance.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Another way enzyme malfunctions can cause disease comes from germline mutations in genes coding for DNA repair enzymes.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Defects in these enzymes cause cancer because cells are less able to repair mutations in their genomes.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] This causes a slow accumulation of mutations and results in the development of cancers.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] An example of such a hereditary cancer syndrome is xeroderma pigmentosum, which causes the development of skin cancers in response to even minimal exposure to ultraviolet light.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Similar to any other protein, enzymes change over time through mutations and sequence divergence.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Given their central role in metabolism, enzyme evolution plays a critical role in adaptation.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] A key question is therefore whether and how enzymes can change their enzymatic activities alongside.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] It is generally accepted that many new enzyme activities have evolved through gene duplication and mutation of the duplicate copies although evolution can also happen without duplication.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] In addition, MAP is metal-ion dependent while creatinase is not, hence this property was also lost over time.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Small changes of enzymatic activity are extremely common among enzymes.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] In particular, substrate binding specificity (see above) can easily and quickly change with single amino acid changes in their substrate binding pockets.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] This is frequently seen in the main enzyme classes such as kinases.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Artificial (in vitro) evolution is now commonly used to modify enzyme activity or specificity for industrial applications (see below).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Enzymes are used in the chemical industry and other industrial applications when extremely specific catalysts are required.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] Enzymes in general are limited in the number of reactions they have evolved to catalyze and also by their lack of stability in organic solvents and at high temperatures.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] As a consequence, protein engineering is an active area of research and involves attempts to create new enzymes with novel properties, either through rational design or *in vitro* evolution.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/enzyme] These efforts have begun to be successful, and a few enzymes have now been designed "from scratch" to catalyze reactions that do not occur in nature.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] In biochemistry, **Michaelis–Menten kinetics**, named after Leonor Michaelis and Maud Menten, is the simplest case of enzyme kinetics, applied to enzyme-catalysed reactions involving the transformation of one substrate into one product.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] In 1913, Michaelis and Menten expanded on Victor Henri's fundamental equation of enzyme kinetics, which was established in 1902.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] It takes the form of a differential equation describing the reaction rate v (rate of formation of product P, with concentration p ) as a function of a , the concentration of the substrate A (using the symbols recommended by the IUBMB).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] V , which is often written as $V_{\max }$ , represents the limiting rate approached by the system at saturating substrate concentration for a given enzyme concentration.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] The **Michaelis constant** $K_{\mathrm {m} }$ has units of concentration, and for a given reaction is equal to the concentration of substrate at which the reaction rate is half of V .
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Biochemical reactions involving a single substrate are often assumed to follow Michaelis–Menten kinetics, without regard to the model's underlying assumptions.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Only a small proportion of enzyme-catalysed reactions have just one substrate, but the equation still often applies if only one substrate concentration is varied.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] The plot of v against a has often been called a "Michaelis–Menten plot", even recently, but this terminology is historically misleading, as Michaelis and Menten did not use such a plot.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Instead, they plotted v against $\log a$ , which has some advantages over the usual ways of plotting Michaelis–Menten data.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] If v is the dependent variable, then it does not distort any experimental errors in v .
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Michaelis and Menten did not attempt to estimate V directly from the limit approached at high $\log a$ , something difficult to do accurately with data obtained with modern techniques, and almost impossible with their data.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Instead they took advantage of the fact that the curve is almost straight in the middle range and has a maximum slope of $0.576V$ i.e. $0.25\ln 10\cdot V$ .
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] With an accurate value of V it was easy to determine $\log K_{\mathrm {m} }$ from the point on the curve corresponding to $0.5V$ .
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] This plot is virtually never used today for estimating V and $K_{\mathrm {m} }$ , but it remains valuable to compare the properties of several enzymes across a broad range of substrate concentrations - such as isoenzymes.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] For example, the four mammalian isoenzymes of hexokinase are half-saturated by glucose at concentrations ranging from about 0.02 mM for hexokinase A (brain hexokinase) to about 50 mM for hexokinase D ("glucokinase", liver hexokinase), spanning a 2500-fold range.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] A conventional (linear) plot would compromise on readability for the high-affinity isoenzyme graphs, but a semi-logarithmic plot allows to read off the kinetic parameters for all isoenzymes.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] A decade before Michaelis and Menten, Victor Henri found that enzyme reactions could be explained by assuming a binding interaction between the enzyme and the substrate.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] His work was taken up by Michaelis and Menten, who investigated the kinetics of invertase, an enzyme that catalyzes the hydrolysis of sucrose into glucose and fructose.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] In 1913, they proposed a mathematical model of the reaction.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] It involves an enzyme E binding to a substrate A to form a complex EA that releases a product P regenerating the original form of the enzyme.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] in which $e_{0}$ is the initial enzyme concentration.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] The reaction order depends on the relative size of the two terms in the denominator.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] At low substrate concentration $a\ll K_{\mathrm {m} }$ , so that the rate $v={\frac {k_{\mathrm {cat} }e_{0}a}{K_{\mathrm {m} }}}$ varies linearly with substrate concentration a (first-order kinetics in a ).
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] However at higher a , with $a\gg K_{\mathrm {m} }$ , the reaction approaches independence of a (zero-order kinetics in a ), asymptotically approaching the limiting rate $V_{\mathrm {max} }=k_{\mathrm {cat} }e_{0}$ .
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Further addition of substrate would not increase the rate, and the enzyme is said to be saturated.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] The Michaelis constant $K_{\mathrm {m} }$ is not affected by the concentration or purity of an enzyme.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Its value depends both on the identity of the enzyme and that of the substrate, as well as conditions such as temperature and pH.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] The model is used in a variety of biochemical situations other than enzyme-substrate interaction, including antigen–antibody binding, DNA–DNA hybridization, and protein–protein interaction.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] It can be used to characterize a generic biochemical reaction, in the same way that the Langmuir equation can be used to model generic adsorption of biomolecular species.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] When an empirical equation of this form is applied to microbial growth, it is sometimes called a Monod equation.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Michaelis–Menten kinetics have also been applied to a variety of topics outside of biochemical reactions, including alveolar clearance of dusts, the richness of species pools, clearance of blood alcohol, the photosynthesis-irradiance relationship, and bacterial phage infection.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] The equation can also be used to describe the relationship between ion channel conductivity and ligand concentration, and also, for example, to limiting nutrients and phytoplankton growth in the global ocean.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] The specificity constant $k_{\text{cat}}/K_{\mathrm {m} }$ (also known as the *catalytic efficiency*) is a measure of how efficiently an enzyme converts a substrate into product.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Although it is the ratio of $k_{\text{cat}}$ and $K_{\mathrm {m} }$ it is a parameter in its own right, more fundamental than $K_{\mathrm {m} }$ .
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Diffusion limited enzymes, such as fumarase, work at the theoretical upper limit of 108 – 1010 M−1s−1, limited by diffusion of substrate into the active site.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] The capacity of an enzyme to distinguish between two competing substrates that both follow Michaelis–Menten kinetics depends only on the specificity constant, and not on either $k_{\text{cat}}$ or $K_{\mathrm {m} }$ alone.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] and so the ratio of rates depends only on the concentrations of the two substrates and their specificity constants.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Although Henri derived the equation he made no attempt to apply it.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] In addition, Michaelis and Menten understood the need for buffers to control the pH, but Henri did not.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Parameter values vary widely between enzymes.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] in which *e* is the concentration of free enzyme (not the total concentration) and *x* is the concentration of enzyme-substrate complex EA.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] where $e_{0}$ is now the total enzyme concentration.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] where $K_{\mathrm {diss} }=k_{-1}/k_{+1}$ is the dissociation constant of the enzyme-substrate complex.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Likewise with the assumption of equilibrium the Michaelis constant $K_{\mathrm {m} }=K_{\mathrm {diss} }$ .
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] When studying urease at about the same time as Michaelis and Menten were studying invertase, Donald Van Slyke and G.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Cullen made essentially the opposite assumption, treating the first step not as an equilibrium but as an irreversible second-order reaction with rate constant $k_{+1}$ .
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] and to note that it is functionally indistinguishable from the Henri–Michaelis–Menten equation.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] One cannot tell from inspection of the kinetic behaviour whether $K_{\mathrm {m} }$ is equal to $k_{+2}/k_{+1}$ or to $k_{-1}/k_{+1}$ or to something else.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Haldane undertook an analysis that harmonized the approaches of Michaelis and Menten and of Van Slyke and Cullen, and is taken as the basic approach to enzyme kinetics today.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] They assumed that the concentration of the intermediate complex does not change on the time scale over which product formation is measured.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] This is the generalized definition of the Michaelis constant.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] All of the derivations given treat the initial binding step in terms of the law of mass action, which assumes free diffusion through the solution.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] However, in the environment of a living cell where there is a high concentration of proteins, the cytoplasm often behaves more like a viscous gel than a free-flowing liquid, limiting molecular movements by diffusion and altering reaction rates.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Although this gel-like structure severely restricts large molecules like proteins, its effect on small molecules, like many of the metabolites that participate in central metabolism, is very much smaller.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] In practice, therefore, treating the movement of substrates in terms of diffusion is not likely to produce major errors.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Nonetheless, Schnell and Turner consider it more appropriate to model the cytoplasm as a fractal, in order to capture its limited-mobility kinetics.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] By plotting reaction rate against concentration, and using nonlinear regression of the Michaelis–Menten equation with correct weighting based on known error distribution properties of the rates, the parameters may be obtained.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Before computing facilities to perform nonlinear regression became available, graphical methods involving linearisation of the equation were used.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] A number of these were proposed, including the Eadie–Hofstee plot of v against $v/a$ , the Hanes plot of $a/v$ against a , and the Lineweaver–Burk plot (also known as the double-reciprocal plot) of $1/v$ against $1/a$ .
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Of these, the Hanes plot is the most accurate when v is subject to errors with uniform standard deviation.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] From the point of view of visualizaing the data the Eadie–Hofstee plot has an important property: the entire possible range of v values from 0 to V occupies a finite range of ordinate scale, making it impossible to choose axes that conceal a poor experimental design.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] However, while useful for visualization, all three linear plots distort the error structure of the data and provide less precise estimates of v and $K_{\mathrm {m} }$ than correctly weighted non-linear regression.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Assuming an error $\varepsilon (v)$ on v , an inverse representation leads to an error of $\varepsilon (v)/v^{2}$ on $1/v$ (Propagation of uncertainty), implying that linear regression of the double-reciprocal plot should include weights of $v^{4}$ .
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] This was well understood by Lineweaver and Burk, who had consulted the eminent statistician W.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Edwards Deming before analysing their data.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Unlike nearly all workers since, Burk made an experimental study of the error distribution, finding it consistent with a uniform standard error in v , before deciding on the appropriate weights.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] This aspect of the work of Lineweaver and Burk received virtually no attention at the time, and was subsequently forgotten.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] The direct linear plot is a graphical method in which the observations are represented by straight lines in parameter space, with axes $K_{\mathrm {m} }$ and V : each line is drawn with an intercept of $-a$ on the $K_{\mathrm {m} }$ axis and v on the V axis.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] The point of intersection of the lines for different observations yields the values of $K_{\mathrm {m} }$ and V .
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Many authors, for example Greco and Hakala, have claimed that non-linear regression is always superior to regression of the linear forms of the Michaelis–Menten equation.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] However, that is correct only if the appropriate weighting scheme is used, preferably on the basis of experimental investigation, something that is almost never done.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] As noted above, Burk carried out the appropriate investigation, and found that the error structure of his data was consistent with a uniform standard deviation in v .
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] More recent studies found that a uniform coefficient of variation (standard deviation expressed as a percentage) was closer to the truth with the techniques in use in the 1970s.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] However, this truth may be more complicated than any dependence on v alone can represent.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Ideally the v in each of these cases should be the true value, but that is always unknown.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] However, after a preliminary estimation one can use the calculated values ${\hat {v}}$ for refining the estimation.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] In practice the error structure of enzyme kinetic data is very rarely investigated experimentally, therefore almost never known, but simply assumed.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] It is, however, possible to form an impression of the error structure from internal evidence in the data.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] This is tedious to do by hand, but can readily be done in the computer.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Santiago Schnell and Claudio Mendoza suggested a closed form solution for the time course kinetics analysis of the Michaelis–Menten kinetics based on the solution of the Lambert W function.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] The above equation, known nowadays as the Schnell-Mendoza equation, has been used to estimate V and $K_{\mathrm {m} }$ from time course data.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Only a small minority of enzyme-catalysed reactions have just one substrate, and even if the number is increased by treating two-substrate reactions in which one substrate is water as one-substrate reactions the number is still small.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] One might accordingly suppose that the Michaelis–Menten equation, normally written with just one substrate, is of limited usefulness.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] This supposition is misleading, however.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] the other symbols represent kinetic constants.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Suppose now that a is varied with b held constant.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] in which $K_{\mathrm {ic} }$ is the competitive inhibition constant and $K_{\mathrm {iu} }$ is the uncompetitive inhibition constant.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Pure non-competitive inhibition is very rare, being mainly confined to effects of protons and some metal ions.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Cleland recognized this, and he redefined *noncompetitive* to mean *mixed*.
[src:enzyme-catalysis/michaelis-menten-kinetics] Some authors have followed him in this respect, but not all, so when reading any publication one needs to check what definition the authors are using.
